comments:
Intel for many years instead of innovating over the years spent large sums of money manipulating the market and corrupting benchmark software. I am mainly addressing the mafia like actions in business that made it so their focus wasn't innovation, but espionage, delaying competition, politics, and many other unfocused not exactly moral focal points.  I am a slouch compared to many highly technical people and I was able to prove years ago Intel was doing this bad stuff and if I can prove it then many others could prove it too but were silenced.  If they spent the massive amount of money that paid people off and robbed the public of wealth they could have invested and even bought ASML from Phillips when it was worthless or even at the beginning of its raise documents show it was for sell.  Good thing they didn't since it would have slowed down the world's tech progress and it would be even more expensive than it is now.  As a stock holder of Intel for many years in stock and mutual like funds, I aspect more of intel and they need to keep cleaning house of their cancers some of the internal politics is the similarly but different thing  that is eating Google and a trend towards more amoral tendencies.  The proof is in the timeline of all the delays and why they are still on the old nanometer sizes while the competitors are on 3nm. All this info you can look up especially if you are willing to not get lost in the weeds. Â

For comparison reasons you can view Intel as Inbred producing genetical damaged offspring where TSMC reached out to the world to consolidate and make chips for everyone and use group resources to do so making the cutting edge technology cheaper.  I am personally a fan of this business model, businesses that are deathly afraid of getting there ideas stolen like Intel since that is how they were founded is embedded in their work model and culture.

author: @MASMIWA
comments:
Interesting with an American bias clearly showing.  The big American semiconductor companies like AMD, Nvidia, Qualcomm, and Apple have their semiconductors made in either TSMC or Samsung.  Rising to compete against these giants are the Chinese, with SMIC the biggest of the bunch in fab.  Huawei's HiSilicon is a leading design company. SMEE is leading China's efforts to develop lithography to compete with ASML.  2024 will see China's rise beyond silicon as SMIC looks to produce 5nm and maybe 3nm chips.  Photonics, graphene, and quantum chips will rise and could possibly replace silicon and achieve functional performance beyond silicon's attempt at 1nm.

Intel achieved 7nm two years ago and SMIC just did. Huawei now has two fabs, one focused on photonics and the other on silicon. China has 44 fabs in production and 12 under construction.  China is replacing the US in mature node semiconductors above 7nm and nibbling away above 7nm. There are media reports that Huawei is organizing the complete semiconductor supply chain so domestic production can be completely Chinese.  China's MIC 2025 appears to be doable in the semiconductor sector as China no longer needs US technology.  In fact, China is number one in international patents for the last 3 years, outpacing the US.

You see the fear in the US government as it attempts to suppress China's semiconductor rise. Literally hundreds of Chinese semiconductor companies have US sanctions placed on them with Huawei taking the crown with the most. The last desperate gasp by the US is to nullify Chinese patents in the US so US companies will not have to pay Chinese patent fees.  It matters not because the Chinese will now become more secretive and we won't know until after the fact what China has achieved.

The TSMC fab in Arizona is halted, it was delayed to 2024 opening and now to 2025.  With China rising in the high end chip sector, there is a good chance it may never open.  Even Intel's super fab in Ohio is questionable.  It has ceased construction and if China can produce 5nm and 3nm chips, it may never see the light of day.  China will compete on price and that drives the economy of semiconductors, everything else being equal.

One thing for sure, the US government is destroying the US semiconductor sector with its sanctions and restrictions. and it is about to destroy the EV sector with its restrictions on subsidies for cars with any link to Chinese battery components. Key to EV batteries is graphite, and the highly refined graphite used in these batteries comes form China. More than 90% of refined graphite comes from China so Biden's attempt to stop Chinese batteries into the US are still born before the word go.

https://globaledge.msu.edu/blog/post/57351/china-is-the-world's-leading-graphite-producer#:~:text=Since%20they%20produce%20most%20of,process%20on%20a%20global%20scale.

Like the US sanctions on Russia, the harm to Russia is minimal and the victim is the EU.  The US will follow as we enter 2024 as the US economy has the potential for a severe recession. There will be no soft landing.

https://www.reuters.com/markets/global-markets-outlook-analysis-pix-2023-12-07/#:~:text=Bond%20giant%20PIMCO%20puts%20the,down%20from%20about%204.3%25%20currently%20.

What the stock pundits have not factored in is the loss of Ukraine and the defeat of Israel in 2024.  The US and EU will be hard pressed to get oil/gas from the Middle East after this debacle.

UPDATE: 08/02/2024 Intel announced it laid off 15,000 of its workforce. Huawei's 920b is said to equal Nvidia's A100 AI chip. China has produced an ultrathin single atom substrate said to give semiconductors higher bandwidth and lower power consumption.  Both TSMC and Huawei are advertising their success at chiplet stacking which increases performance.

author: @PaulYan-j8j
comments:
Taiwan has leveraged unfair policies, including low-cost labor, land subsidies, tax incentives, low electricity and water prices, and a favorable interest rate environment. Additionally, it has benefited from institutional advantages such as low-cost universal education. Seizing the opportunity presented by the semiconductor industry's shift after the US-Japan semiconductor war in the 1980s, Taiwan has vigorously developed the semiconductor manufacturing and chip design industries. Currently, due to the advantages of unfair policies, many semiconductor companies in Taiwan have grown to the extent that they can compete with leading US companies. For example, MediaTek surpassed Qualcomm to become the world's top mobile chip processor company. This success is not solely attributed to MediaTek's capabilities but stems from the unfair competitive advantage.
Given this situation, the United States cannot tolerate the continuation of such circumstances. It is time to counteract and dismantle Taiwan's semiconductor industry, including companies like TSMC and MediaTek.

author: @saswatbharat1107
comments: In the year 2004, each and every body in the world were facing difficulties to develop ITO patterns on glass substrate and on flexible substrates. But we did ITO lithography in such a manner inside yellow room in the presence of UV light that we did not find any defects in ITO patterning. But we took few months and after rigorous testing by Optical Microscope, TENCOR profilometer and Kelvin probe and X Ray Diffraction by AFM we realised the defects and also rectified . This work is Nobel Prize winning work.

author: @saswatbharat1107
comments: Leave other technology. Who did revolution in ITO lithography? Myself - Senior Project Associate and Girija Samal- PhD student at SCDT, IITK in the SCDT, IITK. We two did lots of ITO Lithography and after rigorous experiments we had optimised ITO Lithography inside Yellow Room. This experiments we did under the leadership of Dr. Y. N Mohapatra - Head of SCDT, IITK. For this revolution in ITO Lithography other team devloped Flexible electronics Display where my name is also mentioned. This flexible display paper was published in MRS, Boston after presentation by Dr. Satyandra Kumar. So, we two alongwith Dr. Y. N Mohapatra should get Nobel Prize for ITO Lithography revolution. This is very crucial for Display as well as Chips making.

In 2020, the top exporters of Semiconductor Devices were China ($35.8B), Japan ($9.57B), Malaysia ($8.67B). In 2020, the top importers of Semiconductor Devices were Hong Kong ($16.5B), United States ($12.5B), China ($10.8B).

ðŸ™â¤  What is the CHIPS and Science Act?

The CHIPS and Science Act aims to reduce the countryâ€™s reliance on overseas supply chains. It provides USD 52.7 billion for manufacturing, research, and communications technology security subsidies.

In 1990, the United States manufactured nearly 40% of the worldâ€™s supply of semiconductors. Today, that share is down to 12%. 

U.S. tech giants Nvidia, Google, and Apple rely on Taiwanese foundries for 90% of their chip production.

â€œSo if some force were to disrupt our ability to buy these chips from Taiwan, it would really be an absolute crisis in our ability to protect ourselves,â€ Secretary Raimondo shared with Marketplace.

author: @dgillies5420
comments:
EUV = Extreme UltraViolet (a very high-frequency wavelength of light = smaller details).
The EUV machine is basically a photo-printer using ultraviolet light.
And instead of printing 1 (b/w) layer or 3-layers (red, blue, green) of image, they print up to ~100 layers.
7:00 They use traditional ideas from silk screen printing to print really, really tiny pictures onto silicon.
Often they print onto a layer of metal or silicon, then in a developer step the non-printed areas are etched away, often by simple acids which avoid the EUV-exposed areas (the EUV strengthens a material you want to keep).  Then a new layer of metal or silicon is added and the process repeats.  Sometimes instead of just printing & removing metal, they print, remove metal, then send hot "doping materials" through the printed picture to change properties of the silicon wafer below, making it a "better semiconductor", then they etch away the rest of the metal, and repeat.  Starting in the 1960's, companies were literally using photographic enlargers to print integrated-circuit chips, in 5-10 steps, and making chips & printing photographs was not terribly different.

author: @johndoh5182
comments:
Intel is not stuck on 10nm.  They were stuck at 14nm.  Intel rebranded their process nodes to be in line with TSMC's transistor density which is what matters the most.  So these numbers, 10nm 5nm, etc..... don't mean anything.  They are advertising terms.

So, Intel right now is on the equiv. to TSMC 7nm, actually the name is N7.  So TSMC has a ONE node advantage over Intel, not two.  Intel is supposed to be on their "Intel 4" process node in 2023.  When this happens this puts them much closer to TSMC who will be getting close to being in risk production on their 3nm node, or N3.

There are multiple mistakes in the video.  One is suggesting that Intel has processors made using TSMC.  Actually Intel has contracts from other companies to make chips, and part of the time Intel doesn't have the capacity to so they outsource to TSMC for this, but Intel processors are made on Intel wafers.

Intel IS using TSMC to made their graphics chips for their new line of graphics cards that go into a PC.  This is a new line of products for Intel.

author: @innov4u
comments:
A great feat of engineering and science !
I wonder, however:
a. euv involves high energy photons. As the wavelength decreases, each photon has more energy. Is it possible that such photons create micro fissures or otherwise damage wafers ?
b. The testability problem: is it possible to reliably test the chips, considering their complexity ? 
c. If bugs are later detected by customers, can this decrease their enthusiasm for ever improving performance ?
d. Is this trend truly beneficial to the market ? Do customers need such complex devices ? After all, people want just to communicate, not to send satellites into Space !?

author: @hjf3022
comments: To (D). Yes. Chips that are at the same time more computationally capable, more energy efficient, and made of less material is more valuable than not those things.

a. the wafers aren't really damaged, but higher energy photons don't always land right on target so the shot ends up developing the wrong part of the photoresist sometimes
b. half of what makes these chips complex is that they are literally built to be tested, its 100% possible and necessary
c. not if you fix them
d. market yes, customers maybe, people eh, who needs em

author: @johndoh5182
comments:
This is starting to change.  Intel can make chips cheaper than outsourcing to TSMC, which is why they can now price their CPUs about the same as AMD, but Intel has a higher profit margin.  Now, Intel is still on a 7nm node (not 10), or it's actually called "Intel 7" and they rebranded their naming because the transistor density is comparable to TSMC.

There were a couple points made in this video that were wrong.  Intel does outsource to TSMC and in fact they've done so for years. There are a lot of mistakes in these videos. Here are some.

NASA rovers do not use "5 nm" chips. Space is very heritage focused and thus most ICs that fly in space are at least 20 nm parts, most are 250 nm or more. Processing power for space tends to lag about a decade behind commercial.

There are no "5" or "3" or "7" nm features on these chips. The Intel naming scheme is more honest. These "nodes" are really about logic density increases. One "7 nm" part isn't the same as the others. Intel "10 nm" is closer first generation 7 nm TSMC/Samsung processes in terms of actual density. 

The "chip shortage" during the pandemic was across many sectors. Consumer products like XBOXes and GPUs for bitcoin mining used the more advanced nodes from TSMC. However automotive chip for things other than infotainment, and vision systems are generally 65 nm+ (when these nm number were actual gate lengths). With Micron's target reduction in memory the cyclical nature of the DRAM/FLASH business is showing the consumer market is no longer supply constrained. That actually means leading edge capacity is available. What is not available are things like digital isolators produced by companies like Texas Instruments, Analog Devices/Maxium. 

What is funny about the obsession of the financial reporting about chips is the crazy monolithic focus on digital processing. You need to build a radio for a phone. You need sensors, microphones, cameras. Without the interaction surface to the world which is analog you can do nothing interesting. That interface can be a keyboard or it can be a camera, but it is still not a "leading edge" chip. 

Don't have a leading edge CPU or GPU, your application runs a bit slower. Don't have a digital isolator you cannot make a car at all or a medical device. These things are the chip shortage that matters and the companies are over ordering having moved from just in time supply chains to inventory ones. 

Shortages for things like Neon from the war in Ukraine are important too. ASML didn't needed advanced chips to make their lithography tool they needed microcontroller and 20 nm FPGAs. 

Can Intel catch up in manufacturing? Yes. With the right people hired this can be done. The bigger problem for Intel is actually one of strategy they have really done poorly making choices of what to do outside of computer processors. With lots of half hearted efforts that are folded up and tossed. A pivot to primarily being a foundry that happens to have a successful processor business solves them needing to figure out the consumer and just needs to figure out physical science. They are actually good at that historically so they can get there. In the end the nodes are slowing and will stall out soon enough. Global Foundries didn't quit for no reason. What Intel is trying to do is get scale enough to complete with TSMC in volume. They are also trying to be more than a digital company by buying Tower I think...

author: @Coolgiy67
comments: Electrical engineer here, let me tell yâ€™all what a chip actually is. Itâ€™s a wafer of silicon thatâ€™s been doped with either boron for p-type semiconductor or phosphorus for n-type semiconductor. Putting a P-type and N-type right next to each other creates a PN junction (Metallurgical junction) thereâ€™s some very interesting physics that goes on here but to cut it short it only conducts current in 1 direction. This device is known as a diode, 2 diodes together is a transistor. So they will layer these semiconductors in such a way to make npn or pnp transistors and etch them with lithography. A transistor can basically act as a switch or an amplifier and can be voltage controlled or current controlled depending on the type of transistor (either bjt or fet)

author: @maxheadrom3088
comments:
@@J_a_s_o_n Exactly! I know what he's talking about and I guarantee: it would take a very long comment to explain it all. I'll try, then, to explain what the hell are those 7nm, 5nm, and super ultra violet light is about.

To make these chips we need to create transistors on it. We do this by mixing some material to one region and another material to another region. To do that we coat the silicon disk (waffer) with a plastic that get brittle when light hits it. We then wash the waffer and add the material we want. We repeat the process for how many different regions we need.

The machine used is like a reverse video projector (or, if you're older, a reverse slide projector): it gets a huge image source and projects it on a tine square on the surface of the waffer. To do that we need some special lenses and projectors. There's another problem: we want to get more transistors on the same small square because that saves us waffers and also allows for chips that consume less electricity. The smallest line (thinnest) used started to get so thin it got smaller than the wavelength of visible light - and that means we can't do it with visible light. People started using ultra-violet and x-ray to do that but that is not so easy!

You know how 5GHz wifi doesn't go as far as 2.4GHz? 5GHz has smaller wavelength than 2.4GHz and that causes 5GHz radio signals from wifi to interact more with walls and doors. The kinds of frequency needed to make a 7nm chip are so high the light interacts even with the glass used to make the mirrors! These machines, for those reasons, are so complicated people don't even want to try and develop their own. Even Japan's governement gave up on their attempt. Japan ruled this market in the past, btw - so they were not starting from zero.

I hope I managed to explain a few things that are important to understand the video.

author: @pkuras
comments: The "chip size" language used in these pieces is inaccurate and misleading. The size of the actual chip ("die size") is measured in millimeters, and for the most advanced chips is pretty big - on the order of tens of millimeters across. The width of the smallest microscopic features on the chips - transistor gates and circuit traces, is the nanometer-scale measurement that's used to denote how advanced the process is. And the "7 nanometer, 5 nanometer" scale language used here is really not that accurate anymore. The industry has shifted away from quoting feature size in nanometers, and towards more general "process node" language. Node 5 (what the reporter's copy would call "5 nanometer") is the current state-of-the-art. Node 3 is next. Usually the most advanced "leading edge" chips have a large die size, and, of course, the smallest imprinted features. Less advanced chips "trailing edge" have larger imprinted features, and are often much smaller in die size, because they have far fewer active devices on them. By far, the largest numbers of manufactured semiconductors use trailing edge technology.

author: @alexd5128
comments: Great video! The word, manufacturing, may mislead an average audience to think that this is a low-tech and laborious process. In reality, chip manufacturing demands MORE R&D than designing a chip! A chip designer does NOT get involved in how to build a transistor as small as 2nm (start of the art as of 2024). He leaves it to the black magic at the chip manufacturer. This is where TSMC comes in. A virus is 100 nm. 2nm is 50x smaller than a virus! Though the equipment to manufacture is made in the U.S. and the Netherlands, how to use this equipment is totally up to the chip manufacturers like TSMC. This is like I can buy the same oven that is also used by a world-class chef, but I can't bake award-winning cookies. That chef has his secret recipes, but I follow a standard cookbook. TSMC and its competitors develop these secret recipes, which cost billions of R&D dollars annually. As long as TSMC is the largest manufacturer in the world, it can naturally afford the biggest R&D budget that its competitors can only dream of. As a result, big customers like Apple or Nvidia naturally line up behind TSMC because they want to have the smallest transistors so that they can pack more of them into the same real estate. This monopolistic following ensures TSMC remains the largest, and thus the biggest R&D budget. It's a POSITIVE FEEDBACK LOOP that makes Intel or Samsung can't even come close. Intel and Samsung also have a handicap that TSMC doesn't. These 2 design chips too. In other words, they compete with their own customers! If Intel can produce chips for Apple, it can steal Apple's IP. TSMC only focuses on how to make a transistor as small as possible and thus alleviate the IP theft concern for its customers.

author: @PaulYan-j8j
comments:
Taiwan has leveraged unfair policies, including low-cost labor, land subsidies, tax incentives, low electricity and water prices, and a favorable interest rate environment. Additionally, it has benefited from institutional advantages such as low-cost universal education. Seizing the opportunity presented by the semiconductor industry's shift after the US-Japan semiconductor war in the 1980s, Taiwan has vigorously developed the semiconductor manufacturing and chip design industries. Currently, due to the advantages of unfair policies, many semiconductor companies in Taiwan have grown to the extent that they can compete with leading US companies. For example, MediaTek surpassed Qualcomm to become the world's top mobile chip processor company. This success is not solely attributed to MediaTek's capabilities but stems from the unfair competitive advantage.
Given this situation, the United States cannot tolerate the continuation of such circumstances. It is time to counteract and dismantle Taiwan's semiconductor industry, including companies like TSMC and MediaTek.

author: @thenavigator5889
comments: You wouldn't need to do anything but add MST to the chips to shrink the die.  It would add 50% GM to the bottom line and would solve the chip shortage. On top of that when you meet your capacity for 2 years, swap over to a new PDK on the same node and run Chips with higher performance.  MST is applicable from 180NM to the smallest 2nm chips today.  In fact MST for a modest 2 or 3% royalty can provide a node improvement to leading edge 3NM or 2NM designs... that means You don't need to build a 2nm fab to get the same mobility improvement atomera provides for 3% of selling price.  If it's 20B to build a 2nm fab, why not use mst for 100M a year vs waiting years to build and spending billions.  MST is ready now not 5 years waiting for 2nm fab to come. Must be waiting for Intel and Samsung to adopt first?

author: @SeeMoreLevingthon
comments:
You keep making the mistake that a bigger nanometer-number automatically means bigger chips and that's not true. It can be, but it's not a causal relationship. The coffeemaker chips you mentioned are usually ARM-based or other RISC architecture, aiming at providing the most specialized logic. Specializing it also means cutting out unnecessary logic, so you end up with a smaller die, which lowers cost per chip as you get more chips per wafer AND you get a better yield, as smaller chips are less likely to contain an error that would make them unusable. So, a 14-nanometer specialized CPU might be much smaller than a general compute 7-nanometer consumer CPU, for example. 
This is why it's not correct to say "bigger chips" for chips that have been manufactured on older nodes. Yes, smaller nodes mean smaller transistors OR smaller transistor elements OR less unlogic space OR something related (it's not standardized what it means, by the way) BUT that also means that designers can now keep the chip's size the same while cramming more logic per area unit. So, chips might be getting smaller while keeping the same functionality as before OR they might be keeping their size but add functionality. Heck, they might even get bigger, like Cerebra's WSE. ALSO, if you're talking about chips, you should be able to make the distinction between CPUs and SoCs, for example, and types of chips and packaging.

author: @BlueSharkRides

I am glad TSMC is opening fabs in the US. But placing them in Arizona has to be one of the absolute worst decisions they could have made.

The west is in an absolute severe drought that has lasted 20+ years now. The Colorado river cannot keep up with water usage of Nevada, Arizona, and SoCal. We are losing Powell and are losing Mead.

It would have made much more sense to build these Fabs in Oregon, Idaho, Wyoming or pretty much any Northern state that isn't going to run out of water soon. The tax revenue to Arizona only matter so much if they have a source of clean water and right now on this course it's looking bad. I don't get why they made this decision to build there.

author: @Etheoma
comments:
Ehhhh... nanometres actually don't matter anymore and haven't ever since Intel went FinFET which was like 2011 because nanometres were a measurement of the fin pitch which before finFETs directedly effected density. After FinFETs however from 32 to 22/14nm fin pitches remained mostly untouched, but density did continue to improve, but this meant that the nm measurement become a marketing term rather than an actual measurement of any features, this is most apparent in the move from 22 - 14nm to 7nm which even if you just look at density as a measure of desnity increase it should have been called 12 - 10nm, and 5nm should be 8 - 7nm and 3nm should be 6 - 5nm, but even it's still not 100% accurate because of smaller amount of cheating in the naming 3nm should be closer to 10nm if you were to look at the density increase from 32nm.

Really nobody should be using the term nm anymore and you should use the brand name for each company, Intel even renamed 10nm to Intel 7 because it is equivalent to TSMC N7/"7nm" I don't actually know Samsung's naming for their nodes.

author: @Etheoma
comments: Samsung can make the most advanced chips... humm while that may techically be true, they have always overblown what they can actually reasonably manufacture, so while yes they can techically produce chips which are technically as dense as TSMC, they don't have the same performance characteristics and the yields are that of a node which basically doesn't exist, basically like Intel 10nm was like for the last 5 years.

author: @ArnaudMEURET
comments: Please someone explain the actual strategic benefit when the chips have to be shipped to China for product assembly anyway. AFAIK, no US soil factory uses 5nm chips. Car manufacturers will not use this facility as TSMC wonâ€™t be producing the old chips cars use.

author: @Random-Stranger
comments: The 5nm bleeding edge chips will go to the massive cloud providers and leading edge server farms, along with the hundreds of supercomputer arrays that get updated routinely not just in the US but all over the world.

author: @ArnaudMEURET
comments: @@Random-Stranger Exactly so the dies will have to go to packaging (Philippines?) then motherboard and product assembly (China, Taiwan) and back to the US so whatâ€™s the point of US soil foundries?

author: @Random-Stranger
comments:
@@ArnaudMEURET Cost reduction, improved logistics and supply chain redundancy in case earthquake, massive hurricane or a sudden strike from China hits Taiwan. It takes at least 2 years and 10 billion dollars to set up a fab. Not having any crucial bleeding edge fabs in the US is a weak point in US semiconductor supply, especially with Intel not being competitive for at least 3-5 years at the bleeding edge. Packaging and assembly can also be relocated but you gotta build and ensure you have the fabs up and running first. Once the fabs are up, you can be sure that some of the crucial packaging and assembly will also be relocated in the US. 

The car chips are a drop in the bucket in TSMC's portfolio. The US fabs being built are for the bleeding edge nodes. Those fabs aren't producing any silicon for cars. The older node fabs at Intel and Global Foundries can handle those.

author: @ArnaudMEURET
comments: @@Random-Stranger I sincerely hope your optimistic outlook will become the reality. However I read that the current shortage for car chips is mostly due to existing foundries having lost interest in _old_, 40+nm, less profitable lines and are dragging their feet to set them back up and running on those processes. The hundreds of billions currently being poured into new fabs will take time to bring market effects.

author: @Random-Stranger
comments:
@@ArnaudMEURET The chip shortage for car chips is due to the car manufacturers themselves who cancelled their chip orders so the fabs allocated those chips to other customers. The fabs don't operate on a wafer surplus - a lot of these silicon wafers are ordered years in advance - so when you stupidly cancel your wafer orders - they offer those chip orders to other customers who have the money to pick them up. 

We also got an unprecedented explosion in demand due to the global lockdown so any would-be surplus silicon is immediately picked up. The fabs aren't magically gonna have your wafers for you just because you misjudged the demand on your product end (which is what the bean counters at the car manufacturers did). And the fabs were already running 24/7 prior to the huge demand spike so it's not just a matter of them firing up an idle fab to produce extra chips (and no fab ever is idle - they're constantly producing chips in order to recoup the massive cost of the fab manufacture and generate a profit).

author: @johnuferbach9166
comments:
the problem isn't the availability of the material, the problem is the availability of manufacturing capabilities, aka the world can't produce as much as it would like to use at the moment.. which is why they are all investing to build new fabs in order to increase production capacities... 

and if you meant reuse the chips in the sense of just taking the old ones and putting them in new devices... in theory you could, but most of the components prices is on the order of cents, so it's not worth the effort, and most of these components do very specific things / function a very specific way, so each product usually only works with the chip it's designed to use (for example in a phone you have the more expensive main processor / gpu etc (soc), but then you also have the cameras, the charge controller for the battery, acceleration sensor, light sensor and a whole bunch more, and all of these need to be connected in the right way (aka all the right connections need to go to the right place) and also work with the programming of eachother (for example the charge controller has to tell the processor that the phone is currently being charged, or the acceleration sensor tells the processor where down is currently etc)... so it's all very specific and you can basicly not exchange stuff, unless it's designed to work with a selection of components, which still can't be any but only very specific ones

and then you also have the problem, that new products always need to be more fast, more shiny etc so you always need the newest generation aswell, especially for stuff that is expensive / high performance

author: @waycoolscootaloo
comments:
Good ol Manitowoc Cranes. Built right here in Manitowoc Wisconsin. (Headquartered in Milwaukee WI) The 2,535-ton (31000 series) crane is utterly massive and is as big as a small skyscraper. Of course, this particular crane is only used on the largest of industrial projects and is overkill for almost any job. Hence why Most of the Manitowoc cranes that are purchased are in the 80 to 165-ton range. But Manitowoc has 17 crawler crane models ranging in capacities from 80 ton to 2,535 ton's for the newest and largest model. 

It's also nice to see the US here finally starting to expand domestic chip production. The US is the tech capital, and on the chip production side, we have let our capacity dwindle over the years. But with Intel and TSMC now expanding fabrication plants, the US will reduce its reliance on imports for whatever our domestic manufacturing doesn't quite cover when trying to meet consumer demand.

author: @KuptisOriginal
comments: Yes, it's part of the etching process.  UV is used in the lithography steps where the image for that layer is put on an added substrate.  The substrate is then exposed to the UV light:  areas which are exposed to the UV light harden while the areas blocked from being exposed to the UV light stay soft.  The areas that stay soft are then etched away in the following etching process.

author: @soylentgreenb
comments: There is a major error in this video. There is no 5 nm process, 5 nm is not a length, it is just a name. Nothing on a 5 nm chip is 5 nm; not the contacted gate pitch not the minimum metal pitch and not anything else you can measure on the chip. On 350 nm, you could talk about a 350 nm process; the transistors had 350 nm MMP and 350 nm CGP; they were 350 nm transistors. By traditional measurements you would call TSMCs and 5 nm, Samsungs 5 nm and intels 10 nm as something like 40 or 50 nm process node.

The smallest transistors are approaching ATOMIC scale - gates in current 7/10 nm processes are commonly 50 atoms thick, or in that ballpark.

author: @bricefleckenstein9666
comments:
Dang, so many mistakes in this video.
Chips do NOT have "hundreds of layers", and each layer is NOT a separate transistor.
Perhaps a DOZEN layers (usually a little less) to make ONE layer of transistors.

As a hint - what TSMC and Samsung call "5 nanometer process" is almost identical to what Intel calls "7 nanometer" - just like TSMC/Samsung "7 nanometer" was in actual fact the SAME generation and process specs as Intel "10 nanometer".
No, Intel is NOT that far behind, if at all.

author: @invertexyz
comments:
You realize that "100% chip capacity" means they can't produce chips any faster right? The suspicious thing would be if they were at 50% capacity and companies were claiming shortage.
The fact of the matter is, in the past 10 and especially 5 years, there has been a drastic increase in the amount of products that have chips in them. And on top of that the economies of most developing countries has finally reached a point where many of the citizens can actually get phones and other devices now, the available market has absolutely exploded in the last decade while new FAB production didn't keep up. It kind of blind-sided the industry.

Throw a global lockdown on top of that where hundreds of millions of people start buying electronics because they're spending more time at home or need a better PC to do work from home, and it made the problem even worse. (and nevermind the rise of EVs which require more complicated chips than a traditional gas vehicle, and vehicles in general starting to put what are essentially PCs in the center console.)

1. Invest billions of dollars to buy machines/build factories.

author: @johndoh5182
comments:
The only thing this missed is that Intel plans to not only have their 3m node out by around 2025, but also 2nm in which case they'll be once again leaders in fabrication.  The two new plants Intel are building in AZ are both 2nm plants.  For Intel, the names of those nodes are Intel 3, and then Intel 20A.  Intel is behind right now by one node size, in actual transistor density.  But, they've had an issue with power efficiency with their current latest node, which used to be called a 10nm node.  They've renamed the node Intel 7 since transistor density is on par with TSMC 7nm which is what a lot of the world is using right now as a leading edge node.  Only a couple companies are on TSMC 5nm since it's still in its first year run.  One is Apple.  Apple is a risk partner by making a contract with TSMC when these new nodes are ready.

Intel's fabrication problem has also caused them to lose business to other fabless companies, like AMD.  To counter this, Intel joined Apple in becoming a risk partner for TSMC 3nm which is supposed to start production in 2022.  So, Apple and Intel have the first run of TSMC 3nm.  Intel doesn't have a 5nm node, it has a 4nm node, called Intel 4.  So really by the time 2025 rolls around the world of fabrication is going to be interesting.  I'm pretty sure though most older companies that haven't adopted the latest EUV technology are going to be hard pressed to find customers.  What will happen is the price will drop on nodes as small as 7nm, as 5nm, 3nm and 2nm will be very common by then.  Maybe not 2nm, but certainly 3nm.

Also, Samsung is expanding their capacity in Austin for 5nm fabrication.  So, in about 3 years there should be an abundance of higher quality ICs, and the world is going to need it.  ICs made on 5nm, 3nm and 2nm are going to be much more power efficient.

author: @aoikemono6414
comments: Really a load of self aggrandizing self promoting TSMC crap mostly. Intel and others are not far behind, nor is the nm difference directly comparable on different fab processes. The theoretical nm limit is also being reached, so everyone will eventually bunch up behind the same dead end. The most advanced chips go in phones. When was the last time you complained your phone was too slow? Did you have a problem with the 28nm chip on your phone from five years ago? The current power is unnecessary for mobile devices or applications, and even less necessary on fixed devices. The die shrink has increasingly limited returns and limitations. It's half marketing gimmick. National security or economic viability is not hinged upon having the most bleeding edge, smallest transistors. The same way you won't die if you don't have the latest iphone. Your five year old flatscreen TV isn't somehow obsolete because the newest TVs now are a quarter inch thinner, with even shittier speakers, less ports, and mostly the same image quality.

author: @Back2SquareOne
comments: It is gross negligence that we have allowed so much of our tech to become so dependent upon a single geographically remote source.  I am glad that we are working with TSMC to bring advanced fabrication to domestic production.  On the other hand, it kind of sounds like maybe we are overcorrecting.  The entire world is dumping MASSIVE amounts of cash into creating chip fab capacity around the world.  It seems like there may be huge amounts of over capacity globally if all these investments bear fruit.   Since it seems like fabrication in Asia is likely to be cheaper than in the US for the foreseeable future, we ought be aiming for meeting critical defense and commercial needs but avoid over capacity.  If large amounts of capacity are developed in Korea and Europe, that also reduces our dependence on Taiwan produced chips.  Over correcting and producing lots of excess domestic capacity can make those chips much less competitive cost wise and spells trouble for the financial well being of the companies that operate the domestic fabs.  I would like us to be smart and tactical and not be overly reactive which bring a host of new problems.

author: @johnj8639
comments: TSMC measure's their nodes differently than Intel, all fabs measure differently including Samsung - so going by their proposed measurements does not mean more advanced. TSMC and Samsung decided to use different parameters to measure their nodes, when Intel was clearly far ahead on a more advanced node. TSMC and Samsung chose smaller parameters to measure by so they looked more competitive to Intel. This marketing strategy appeared to actually work - Intel's 10nm node is actually more advanced than TSMC's "7nm" - more comparable to TSMC's 5nm node, and intel's 7nm node is more advanced than anything TSMC currently has (even though it is not currently available intel has functional 7nm wafers). So currently Intel's 10nm node could be considered the most advanced in the world, but only a small line of Intel's CPU's are currently on it.

It's not a stretch at all to believe that semiconductors will only become a larger part of our lives as the years go on, especially with the advancement of A.I, self driving, data centre, HPC etc. Also how can you complain about margins not expanding when they are already fluctuate around 50% to 40% all while maintaining a stellar balance sheet is outstanding by any metric!! And to think TSMC is doing this while at the same time spending aggressively to further widen its moat between itself in its competitors. To give you an idea of how ironclad TSMC's market position is, INTEL themselves even outsource their highest margin chip manufacturing to TSMC!!! The more you dig into this company the more it screams buy. If a company that is the lifeblood of Apple, AMD, mediatek, Nvidia among others isn't surely worth premium valuation p/e of 30 I don't know what possibly could. I'd expect a share price of +/- $200 at some point next year especially considering its long period of consolidation this year which has poised the stock for an explosive breakout.

Secondly, China would not have the time to invade and secure Taiwan before the US, the EU and NATO countries got involved.  Regardless of treaties, etc., these countries are well aware of the problems with Taiwan falling to China. The West would not allow that to happen, and China does not have the military/economy to support a war against the West. It's really as simple as that. Side Note: TSMC is moving some of its manufacturing facilities to the US.

author: @hammertimee777
comments: A successful invasion of Taiwan by China is very low. To invade a country, the invader needs to outnumber the invaded country's army at 2:1. Taiwan has 1.6 million military personnel at any given time. There's no way China can transport 3 million soldiers across the Taiwan strait. On top of that, all natural born Taiwanese citizens are required to go through military training, so many Taiwanese people can pick up a weapon and defend an invasion. Assume that China sends 200,000 troops across the Taiwan Strait to invade Taiwan, they would require 1000 ships just to transport the troops Taiwan. Taiwan's air force and ground missiles can sink half of those ships before they reach the shores of Taiwan. Let's assume half of those troops do arrive on the shores of Taiwan, they would be decimated by the ground defense in Taiwan as there would be plenty of time for Taiwan to prepare as soon as they detect troop being mobilized from China. If 100,000 Chinese soldiers die on the Taiwan Strait trying to invade Taiwan, imagine the uproar from the Chinese people. That would topple the communist government of China. China is experiencing an aging and declining population growth due to its 1 child policy, expensive housing, and recent COVID lockdowns. They cannot risk losing another 100,000 young Chinese in wars. Just based on these factors alone, I cannot see an invasion of Taiwan.

author: @mrhassell
comments: Silicon indeed plays a role in the CCP's long-term strategy for Taiwan, but the story is far more complex. Following Japan's surrender at the end of World War II, the Chinese Civil War broke out. The CCP, led by Mao Zedong, triumphed and founded the PRC on October 1, 1949, with Beijing as its capital. In contrast, the defeated ROC government, led by the Kuomintang, retreated to Taiwan on December 7, 1949, along with approximately 2 million troops, officers, civilians, and refugees, fleeing the Peopleâ€™s Liberation Army. The ROC had intended this move as a temporary measure, hoping to regroup and retake the mainland. However, this never occurred, and Taiwan instead became the center of the ROC's modernization and economic development efforts. China's plan to "reintegrate" Taiwanâ€”a sovereign nation not universally recognizedâ€”aims to influence companies like AMD, Nvidia, and others, including Intel. Despite having their own fabrication plants and production services, these companies rely on TSMC, as does the rest of the semiconductor industry, to operate at scale and meet customer demand.

author: @mrhassell
comments: The Second Sino-Japanese War, a conflict between the Republic of China and the Empire of Japan from 1937 to 1945, was a significant part of World War II. It marked the onset of WWII in Asia. Ironically, the war is more widely recognized for its conclusion with the bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki. Following Japan's surrender, all Samurai swords were confiscated. Among these were ancient, invaluable works of art, destroyed and melted down as symbols of surrender and the loss of power. The people who most resisted the CCP, fled to Taiwan and the surrounding islands, which have been inaccessible to China. To take Taiwan, concludes this long term frustration, or major vexing to the CCP.

author: @makerspace533
comments: I was in TI's Corporate Engineering Center from 1977 to 1978.  Dr. Chang was the Vice President  of the MOS division.  TI was quite successful with the TMS1000 series of microcontrollers.  They second sourced the 8080, and had just released the 9900 and 9980.  I don't think Dr. Chang was convinced about the future of microprocessors at that point.  He once said microprocessors were a passing fad.  That was quite a shock since at that time TI was a leader in the production of dynamic memory.  TI never really did much with microprocessors, instead pouring their energies into DSP's and analog technologies.  TI was a product oriented company, not service, so Dr. Chang's vision of giant fabs (TI called them FEPs) , did not fit in with the rest of TI.  It turns out he was right, producing chips for fabless design companies was a good idea.

author: @brennencox516
comments:
0:29 The CCP/PRC can't take Taiwan back, as it has never been under their control.
The Republic of China was founded in 1912. In 1945, Japan had to give the island of Taiwan to the Republic of China.
In 1949 the KMT (ruling political party of the Republic of China) government and what remained of its military retreated to the island/province of Taiwan, as it was the only safe place left, the only territory they still controlled, from CCP forces.
In 1949 the People's Republic of China (PRC) was founded.
The CCP has never taken or controlled the island of Taiwan. The Qing Dynasty, Japan, and The Republic of China have.

author: @zynzy4u
comments: In this video processor clock speed is conflated with processor performance.  One thousand times a clock speed does in no way assure one thousand times the performance.  As an old example, there  was a long standing battle between the speed of processing of the Z80 and 6502 processors.  The Z80 could run at 8MHz and the 6502 ran at 1Mhz.  Many believed the Z80 was therefore faster based on the single metric of clock speed.  This was false.  The 6502 used a single clock cycle to perform a read, execution, and write cycle meaning the 6502 could perform one million instructions per second.  On the other hand, the Z80 has almost no instructions  requiring less than four cycles meaning to perform the same action as the 6502 requires at least twelve cycles making the Z80 substantially slower than the 6502.  RISC and pipeline processors along with parallel processors are very fast compared to the CISC processors.  Keep that in mind while comparing processor performance.

author: @nipponkaijikyokai

author: @paulmichaelfreedman8334
comments: There will never be a race to picometer. The smallest possible transistor (theoretically) is two silicon atoms large which is also the lattice cell unit and is 540 pm in size. And even that is probably not practically possible due to quantum effects completely scrambling the signal, so multiple cell units will always be needed pushing the size of the transistor over 1 nanometer at least. But it seems the shrinking process is just about at the end of the line. Current developments are looking at stacking transistors in a 3-dimensional structure but that immediately brings up heat flow issues, so there is a long way to go on that.

author: @CA-em1kf
comments: I used to work in the forwarding and supply chain industry.  I knew of my colleagues who were asked a few times to personally hand-carry TSMC chips say to Finland (if I remember it correctly, Nokia?) and other countries of destinations because the chips were so urgently required for the production lines.   Depending on the terms of the trade or reasons for the delay, either the buyer or TSMC had to pay for the hand-carry fee, the airplane ticket, the fees for the carrier's days of absence at work...etc.  (which usually takes 2-5 days round trip back to Taiwan).   It had to be done very in a very speedy and professional fashion for the whole process.

author: @binghamkuang
comments:
Fun fact:
Transportation is always miserable in Taiwan, regardless of any city except for Taipei.
We use cars often, so we build road only for cars, which is a big problem that gained attention from public in recent years.

My father is currently working in one of the semiconductor equipment supplier, so TSMC fabs in Tainan is usually some of the destinations of the week before work.
Our family lives in Taichung, and he usually gets stuck in traffic jam on roads. After knowing this, I was wondering : why not just fix the traffic problem by building more convenient public transportation? We can save those smart brains from those pointless jams every day!
Well the harsh truth is, we are a group smart brain, smart but cheapâ€¦

Also, it is important to think about is : we lives in the democratic community, which public constructions is hard the be built by the government, since there is always a need to convince people who owns the land.      Tainan metro system is now under  planning and discussion, with years or even decades to be buildâ€¦, but still, reminds me that we donâ€™t lives in the control of the communist party, which jam is waaaaaay better than that.


By a Taiwanese college student.

author: @johndoh5182
comments:
TSMC's construction site in AZ has the space for expansion.  In fact it can basically be the same as 6 fabs, or maybe in reference to terms used here, 6 stages.  I think N5 is going to be really big so I'm betting TSMC creates 2 N5 and variants of N5 there, and then they probably build N3 capacity there because THAT node is going to be bigger than N5.  And, in case people are wondering how I'm saying this, N5 actually has a cost advantage over N7 unless TSMC raises prices too much.  It's an excellent node with a good balance of frequency range and power scaling along that frequency range and it's a bit better than N7.  It's a node that many companies can use for a step down from HPC products once HPC moves off of N5.  N3 on the other hand is going to be a premiere node, outstanding power savings for low to medium speed devices and TSMC knows it has to clock very fast for HPC.  I don't know what it's going to look like at high frequencies because I don't know of examples of it out in the wild.  On the other hand N5 is now out of risk production with the original risk partners and moving into wide scale adaption, with AMD said to be the biggest customer for N5, based on current contracts.  If it's just as good as N5 at very high frequencies like 5.5GHz then N3 is going to be sufficient for many years for that class of electronics right below HPC.

HPC always moves to the most advanced node.  Companies HAVE to do this to get a competitive edge.  You can look as Apple products.  Their new M2 laptops can run at full speed when switched to battery power.  That's REALLY impressive, and the battery lasts a long time running heavy loads.  And that's using an advanced N5 node, N5P.  They were supposed to be on N3, but N3 isn't ready for risk partners until next year.  I would have thought they would have moved to N4, but I guess N5P is giving excellent performance at frequencies Apple uses which is slower than Intel and AMD, while using little power.

The next step down is N2.  It's possible that even N2 could make it into that AZ complex.  This is the point where probably TSMC goes with the naming format Intel is using, off of nanometer and onto angstrom.  So, the step down from N2 is not N1, that jump is dramatic, so N2 will probably get a name based on angstrom so maybe N20A.  The next node will probably be N17A or N18A.

And here we get into all kinds of physics problems and really just how fast the fabs need to move to smaller nodes.  The efficiency of a 2nm or 20A node is going to be FAR superior to to current N7 or N5 based devices, or in the case of Samsung with their JUST releases devices, 4nm.  It's going to be at the point where a laptop can run a heavy load on battery for many hours.  Right now for instance, Apple M2 based systems will run a heavy load (all-core loads) ON battery and it doesn't reduce clock frequency so it's still consuming the same amount of power.  Apple didn't see the need to drop the frequency to conserve battery.  It's on N5P.  The systems it was compared to was a Zen 3+ laptop and an Intel 12th gen laptop.  They had to drop the frequency to conserve power.  AMD is on TSMC N6 and Intel is on their Intel 7 node.  But 20A is going to use SO little power and the transistor density SO great that once there, Intel, Samsung and TSMC can focus on improving the quality along with coming out with similar size nodes but different characteristics for a wide variety of use cases and I expect that once HPC has moved to N3, there's going to be a slowdown in replacing equipment because of the power savings.  So purchasing is going to slow once we're at N3 and 20A.

HPC based on those nodes could include CPUs that could theoretically have 300 - 500 cores, a SINGLE CPU. N5 is going to allow AMD to produce server CPUs that are 128 cores/256 threads.  But, this is almost full X86-64 cores.  Once the move is made to big-little and AMD figures out the right ISA and can reduce core size to 1/4 that of a full X86-64 core with all the advanced features, even that 128 core CPU could now be 512 cores if it was ALL little cores, on N5!!!!

So N3 and 20A are going to allow HPC to advance to almost unimaginable performance capability.  The problem becomes the rest of the hardware platform.  Do you have enough memory channels for that many cores, is there enough data bandwidth into and out of the CPU.  I'd say power is an issue, but each drop in transistor size comes with reduced power, and if AMD can make a 128 SMT core CPU on N5, then surely they could make a 500+ core monster on N3 using big-little of some type, mostly little cores if they can figure out a memory scheme to deal with that many cores.  And if not on N3, they can easily do it with 20A.

Sorry this is long, won't be read by most people, but it's a lot of food for thought.

author: @Leshic2
comments:
Haha..
Working for an equipment company, I lived in Taiwan for almost 3 years, spending most of my time in these fabs.
Your comment brough memories of seeing unprepared Americans in Taiwan.. Haha..
Learn to use Chop-sticks, really well.  Cafeteria food often has no western silverware (at least 20yrs ago it didn't), and the chop sticks are all smooth, slippery aluminum.
I loved it and loved my time in Taiwan.

The TSMC fabs, sometimes will have a Starbucks in them, and they usually have a side restaurant, next to their cafeteria that serves food that Westerners prefer.
You'll ALWAYS find a large 7-eleven, that more resembles a mini-Wal-Mart, than 7-eleven.  It's often the goto for clothing, bathroom supplies, etc, because you work so sooo many hours.  People who work at all the fabs, essentially live there, and are rarely home.
Afternoon naps are common place too.

20yrs ago, in Tainan (far from the fabs) there was an outstanding Austrian Restaurant, who served amazing German sausages...
As well, a western bar/restaurant called 1st Base, owned by a former Los Angels Dodgers baseball player.
He later opened up a night club called 2nd Base.
This was all 20yrs ago though.

author: @Leshic2
comments:
One more thing...
Funny story..

You may, or may not already know, but "Hello" in Mandarin "Nee-how" or "Nee-how-ma"

Once, in my hotel, at the bar, I found a Westerner.
Didn't see Westerners often back then.  He looked American and I could hear him speaking with a Texan accent..

Patted him on the back, shood his hand and said, "NEE-HOW-MA!!"  with enthusiasm...
He replied with his Texas accent,
NEEEE - HOWDY!!!

Though nothing technical in this video, somehow it shortens the distance between chips and me.

Btw, I was born and grew up in Tainan till my teenage.  Tainan in some way is special in Taiwan.  Many of my friends like my Taiwanese speaking.  They say Tainan folks speak the most elegant Taiwanese ðŸ˜Š.

It is also the place Dutch built their colonial government 4 centuries ago.  The first real government in Taiwan history.  You still can visit the fort and government buildings built by Dutch today.  They are very well maintained.  And some of my childhood friends have red hair, something from Dutch gene pools.

author: @Leshic2
comments:
Very cool!   Red hair.  Wow.
I still remember visiting the fort and old government building when I spent many many months there (20yrs ago).
One thing that always stuck in my mind was at the top of one of the buildings was 4? or was it 5? flags..  I think 4.
and it was all 4 different flags that had ruled Taiwan in the Past.
Dutch, I believe Portugal, Japan, and China?   God, it was so long ago...

I remember being so confused... the Dutch were here?!?!

author: @ideastshoa6383
comments:
@@Leshic2 I don't know about the flags.  There have been several countries setting up governments in Taiwan.  At the beginning there were Dutch in southern Taiwan (i.e. Tainan) and Spanish in northern Taiwan (Tamsui.  Spanish fort is still there too.  It's an even more popular tourist point than the Dutch fort in Tainan).  Then Chinese Ming dynasty in Tainan.  Then Qing dynasty in Tainan.  But all these governments only ruled part of Taiwan, not the whole island.  In 1895 Japan established the first government that really governed the whole island.

After WWII USA defeated Japan (and Japan gave up owning Taiwan) but didn't want to govern Taiwan (not sure if they regret about that now) and asked KMT in China to "manage" Taiwan for its convenience.  Then KMT lost the Chinese civil war and fled to Taiwan and accidentally created a rather complicated situation now.  But a basic reality is People's Republic of China never rules Taiwan even for one second.  Therefore the so called re-unification is a fake issue.  How can one reunify with something that was never part of it?

Portuguese were the first European discovered Taiwan and gave Taiwan the name of Formosa ("beautiful island" in Portuguese), but they probably never setup any settlement.

author: @Leshic2
comments:
@@ideastshoa6383 Thank you for the additional clarification pre-WW2.  Interesting..
That's the first time I've ever heard anybody say that it wasn't until Japan, that anybody really ruled the entire island.

I've done a lot of research on Taiwan (I'm sure not as much as you).

Yes, post WW2, that's been the conclusion I found too.  I'm glad it aligns with you.

It was essentially given to nobody.
KMT was only responsible for taking the Japanese off it, but not given ownership of it.

author: @kirillvourlakidis6796
comments: Fabulous video (pun intended)! I just want to add something to think about. If anyone thinks that Russia's technological gap is limited to IC / micro-electronics, they are very much mistaken. Russia's technological gap is endemic. The F22 was designed in the 1980s and built in the 1990s when feature size was still measured in microns (1000s of nano-meters). The space shuttle was designed in the 70s and built in the 80s, when feature size was 10s of microns. If Russia had the material science, design engineering, systems integration, logistics, administration and business planning skills at an internationally competitive level, and the only thing that they lacked was an IC industry capable of producing <65nm components, they would still be capable of producing incredible, internationally competitive products in the military, scientific or consumer domains. However, they don't. It's a mistake to think that just because the Soviet Union excelled in some of those areas (e.g. material science), that Russia retained those skills. They didn't. The industrial sector collapsed after 1991. All capable professionals left to pursue a better life abroad. The political system which formed after 1991 made it hostile to everything but the most rudimentary industry (e.g. natural resource extraction). There is almost no secondary or tertiary industry left in Russia, and the service sector is laughable. The attempts to kick-start these industries (like the companies talked about in this video) serve a two-fold purpose - to show on national TV that "we can be independent from the West" and to steal money from government contracts and then declare bankruptcy without actually shipping anything. It's a game they play at the higher levels of government in Russia, and have been playing for a long time.

author: @clutteredchicagogarage2720
comments:
I'm going to throw out a bunch of unrelated thoughts. 

(1) I don't know enough about chip fab equipment to be able to gauge whether, for example, the Russian regime could bribe a company in (e.g.,) India to help them import some key equipment (e.g., originally from ASML) in violation of sanctions to help them advance their chip-making. I believe that they will likely try.

(2) Since the Trump government in the USA increased sanctions against China, I've started to wonder if these sanctions could hasten RiscV research in China (and also Russia). I haven't followed this closely, but it appears that other people who follow RiscV R&D closely also believe that this is possible. Just as Linux, due to being truly open source, transitioned from a niche hobby + research OS to overtake proprietary Unix operating systems in usage, I think it's possible that RiscV's adoption could exceed ARM's in 15 years. In the west, I read that Google is investing in RiscV R&D pretty heavily, and I believe Chinese companies will inevitably continue to advance RiscV adoption as well. I think it's possible that millions of android phones could run on RiscV within a few years -- especially in China.

(3) As you said, Russia doesn't need < 20nm computers to manufacture weapons systems. I wholeheartedly hope that sanctions against Russia will make it impossible for the country to ramp up manufacturing of all computerized weapons systems (modern tanks with night-vision and superior aiming technology, new military aircraft, various kinds of missile and rocket systems, etc), but I think that Russia will probably be able to evade sanctions to be able to get microprocessors for equipment that doesn't need many chips. I'd suspect that new aircraft will be difficult to manufacture, but, unfortunately, I think Russia will still be able to make many kinds of military systems by evading sanctions on limited stocks of components obtained from unsanctioned countries.

(4) As a software developer, I've been impressed by software developers in Russia that have excelled in developing highly efficient open source server software. The nginx web server and ClickHouse are a couple examples. I am speculating here, but I believe that computer science education in Russia developed an emphasis on efficient coding in C/C++ at least in part because the performance of computers available in Russia has historically been behind the performance of computers available in the USA or western Europe. I also have a theory that the grammatical structure of slavic languages, in which the declension of nouns and adjectives allows reordering of the subject, verb and object in sentences without loss of meaning, also helps slavic programmers learn functional languages and higher-order functions. This is, I believe, the same reason that reverse-polish notation in math was developed by a Polish mathematician since it is is not unnatural or uncommon for Polish (or Russian or Ukrainian, etc) speakers to express certain ideas in Verb-subject-object order.

author: @vladimirnikolskiy
comments: The Institute of Applied Physics of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IPF RAS) in Nizhny Novgorod is developing the first Russian lithography unit for the production of ultra-small nanometer microelectronics. This is reported on the website "Development Strategy of the Nizhny Novgorod region". At the moment, scientists of the Russian Academy of Sciences have created the first demonstration sample of equipment. At this installation, separate images were obtained on substrates with a resolution up to the maximum 7 nm. The optical system of the demonstrator assembled at the IPF RAS already surpasses all analogues existing in the world today, says Nikolay Chkhalo, Deputy Director of the Institute of Microstructure Physics of the Russian Academy of Sciences for Scientific and Technological Development. Compared, for example, with the lithographs of the largest manufacturer of lithographic equipment for the microelectronic industry, ASML, in the Nizhny Novgorod model, the radiation source is many times more compact and cleaner in operation, Chkhalo noted. According to him, the latter circumstance significantly affects the cost, size and complexity of the equipment.

author: @zahrans
comments:
Because the need there was not Quality but Quantity. Remember, unlike the US, the Soviet Union was still recovering from devastating events that occupied a good chunk of the previous century. from the bolshevik revolution, WWI, famines and then WWII which killed 25 000 000 give or take (some historians est a higher figure). Add to that an enormous portion of the population was still in desperately wretched dirt poor living conditions, not much better from the serfdom their ancestors were released from just a century back. 

There were many terrible wrongs and injustices in the Soviet Union but one of the most commendable things that happened under that rule was that those people was lifted from the aforementioned dirt poor to a reasonable living standards in just a few decades. No, they were not provided with western quality goods but it wasn't a issue. They finally at least HAD goods now like a TV, vaccum cleaner or even cars, _luxuries_ unimaginable to an ordinary Soviet just a few decades back (no matter how laughable those items seem now to modern western eyes). Who knows, if the Soviet Union continued to last we might have seen the focus eventually turn from Quantity to Quality. (although it must be said, Yunost TVs was built pretty solidly, over engineered even!)

According to online data the main chip imports for Russia during the period between 2017 and now are in fact from Infineon (Germany). Most memory imports are from Samsung and Micron/Elpida. Why Russia can't replace TSMC? 
The answer is simple - because they never really needed them.

In any business u have to consider the costs and profits, no company or business can survive without a profit and TSMC has been able to provide their foundry services turnkey to their customers efficiently and higher yields than anyone else hence it is the leading foundry in the world!
Now that the business climate has changed with the Russia sanctions and also the Chinese sanctions by the US, both China and Russia will have to bite the bullet and start their own home ground semiconductor manufacturing and the best part is that they have to do it and succeed otherwise they will be even more behind in technology. 
Another approach is to move away from silicon substrates into maybe graphite which than is a more leveling playing field for both China and Russia.
But time will tell how this plays out but suffice to say, both Russia and China has to succeed otherwise they will forever be at the mercy of US sanctions.
So its not why Russia cant replace TSMC that shouldn't even be the question because TSMC is uncatchable and no foundry in the world has been able to catchup to TSMC given their extremely aggressive customer driven sales strategy to work with their customers and provide their foundry services with fantastic yields! author: @billwhoever2830
comments:
"guns dont need a 7nm chip" is the most accurate statement.
Russia failing to compete with the US, EU and China in latest tech equipment will mean they will have far lower compute power.
This will mainly limit their AI training, science research and maybe server capabilities.
Missiles do not use general purpose cpus.
Missiles and most equipment of any kind nowdays use "ASIC" chips (Application-specific integrated circuit). ASIC chips are usualy far cheaper and more performant on the one thing they are designed to do. They also use far less power and have near to no bugs-crashes-failures. ASICs put on missiles usualy are at a higher lithography for many reasons:
1) lower cost
2) resistance to noise, more reliable in factories or aplications with too much noise (a military missile)
3) heat is far more easily dealt with, no heatsinks or coolers required

In case to produse a decent ASIC you need:
1) Highly skilled engineers
2) Fabs to produse
3) A large amount of devices using them

Most of the cost of an ASIC product goes to the software and hardware engineering because they are very specific to the application and cannot be used in any other device.
If you fail to get a large production of the final product then your "design cost" went to waste.

Here is a short explanation of BAE and why they use ASICs, note that BAE refer to asics as SOCs, this means that system memore (RAM), storage (SSD) and other parts of a normal computer are all inside the chip (with very small capcities, just enough to do the specific job):
https://www.baesystems.com/en-us/definition/what-are-asics

author: @deang5622
comments:
A lot of what you say about ASICs is rubbish. I used to design them.

The cost of an ASIC is dominated by three things: the NRE charge that has to be paid up front to the ASIC vendor to cover the design validation and layout, pre and post layout simulations, generation of automatic test data if the customer has requested it, and the fabrication and testing of the engineering samples.

All this is done before full scale production occurs.
The second factor is chip testing and burn-in for military applications which isn't done for consumer products.

The third factor is the physical size of the chip, the die itself.

The military market is much smaller in terms of the number of chips they buy compared to the consumer product market, so they don't manufacturer as many chips, so that NRE charge is spread over a smaller production quantity of chips meaning the unit price per chip becomes higher.

author: @aoikemono6414
comments: I was reminded of a video by reallifelore trying to explain the importance of TSMC, especially in regards to China. Unfortunately it was so badly researched and the topic so poorly understood, what little credibility he had was completely lost. He oversimplified the point to create a black and white picture that those above 10nm were living in the stone age and those below 10nm were going to rule the world. It's about the dumbest assertion imaginable. He also completely ignored Samsung and Intel, who clearly fit or exceed that 10nm threshold. The world would be slightly less advanced, for a short time at least, if TSMC were to magically disappear, but the world won't stop spinning and technology won't stop advancing. And it most definitely isn't relevant for most major military applications. Much like you don't need a 7nm chip in a gun to shoot it, you also don't need the most advanced processor node in any well researched and long-developed military technology. Even game consoles with much longer development cycles than a typical same-y smartphone don't use the latest stuff.

author: @Redsson56
comments: ASML is a very accomplished and outstanding company (spin off from Philips). But by describing it as Dutch, it seems to imply the EUV technology capability was all from the Netherlands. Many developed democratic countries made many critical EUV subsystem and technical contributions.  And many companies from these countries such as Intel and Samsung provided a lot of direct capital investment. A great example of how the free world works. There have been many brilliant Chinese and Russian scientists and engineers but very few if any significant contributions to semiconductor technology from these non-democratic states. SMIC buys its advanced equipment from Democracies and acquires technical know-how by hiring key people from places like Taiwan. In your other videos you explain the important background clearly. But here I believe you imply too much credit for indigenous technology development to Russia and the PRC. Their people certainly have the inherent capability. The fault lies with their suppressive, corrupt autocratic state systems.  Semiconductor technology is key to weapons development. Russia and China are threatening the democratic world with terrible military violence. We should not enable these Autocracies.

            Intel is building several semiconductor fabs in the US, and are projected to be online in time for carving out its share of the inflated price.

author: @nighttime9539
comments:
The real reason is huge levels of corruption and the fact that the government does not really care about how and where the final product will be used. Even if it's going to get finished, which is rare itself. The scheme is the following: 
1) Rosnano finances a company that is supposed to create something, say a microprocessor (see Elbrus and Baikal).
2) Some work is being done, while the company that got financed (and the whole hierarchy of people that stands between that company and Rosnano) is slowly stealing money from the allocated budget. Maybe not the whole "company" is stealing, but rather "some people in that company".
3) People in the company who steal those money pay back to Rosnano to keep them happy so they don't compain and don't dig in to find out why the progress on the project is so slow or why nothing gets done. 
4) At the end, even if the product design is finished (which is rare), the small batch gets produced (say, 50 microprossesors).
5) The journalists film it and show it on central TV channels with a lot of bullshit like "Russian scientists have produced a cutting-edge superpowerful microprocessors. USA has nothing like it and will be buying from us because they don't have a choice. Russian science and microelectronics are the most powerful now", etc.... 
6) Rosnano reports to the higher management (government) that the final product has been developed and produced.
7) Everybody is happy.

So what's the result of all this? In most cases nothing ever gets created or produced. Even if it does, it's going to be a small amount of product (for example, 50 microprossesors) just to show that "something was done", but in 99% of cases this stage wont' even happen (nevermind mass production). And what happens to the budget of the project (millions of US dollars)? See above.

You might ask: why does Russian government keep spending money on those dead projects if nothing gets done anyway? Because, as I mentioned before, the government itself is a participator in the corruption and money stealing. Creating something is not the main priority here, but rather to receive a big budget and then steal it while pretending to be doing something useful. That's how nanotechnology projects financing works in Russia and a lot of other post-soviet coutries (unfortunately).
