author: @SkyWKing
comments:
I wonder if being able to build leading edge or close to leading edge nodes are really that important for a nation. Most chips made on leading edge nodes are 'nice-to-have' products that are not crucial to national security, industrial capacity or even daily life quality. An overwhelming majority of chips used in the world are not manufactured on leading edge. A pariah state like Russia could sustain itself perfectly fine if it could build lots of 65nm chips. You may say AI or supercomputing but let's say if 65nm is 25x less efficient than leading edge 7nm, what's stopping them from building a computer 50x bigger and more power hungry (after all, energy efficiency is not a concern for them). Russians are experts at overcoming technological disadvantages with brute force. 

From an economics perspective every leading edge node after 14nm has not dramatically reduced performance per unit price. SMIC expanding 14nm could be enough for China/Russia to last quite a long time. Many people are still using smartphones/computers with chips made on 28nm. Having a slow phone or computer did not stop them from accessing latest modern entertainment or productivity software.

author: @talltroll7092
comments: Yes, it matters. For Russia, military applications are currently something of a priority, and the size/weight/power consumption/heat of the electronics they can acquire at scale are pretty important. To be able to build the various advanced missile and tank/plane subsystems that they need to compete with non-Russian equipment, they need something better than 65nm tech. Otherwise, they are back to building Cold War era Soviet designs, and large sections of their military capabilities are going to be stuck at circa 1980s' levels forever

author: @unatco6554
comments: @@talltroll7092 modern military hardware does not use 14nm chips nor are they designed with to require such chips. Certainly not in Russia. They have been able to consistently churn out newer weapons systems with completely domestic supply chains much to the dismay of the west. However they also have some ways to go with Putin investing billions into domestic chip manufacture but its only a matter of time.

author: @RayTsou
comments:
I vaguely have an EE background but to answer your question "what's stopping them from building a bigger chip" is basically latency.

So when people refer to Xnm fab process, what it traditionally refers to is the gate length, or the distance from the source to drain within a transistor. When the gate is ON, current flows from source to drain and once there is enough charge in the drain, the transistor is read as a 1. Now the longer the gate is, the longer it takes for the transistor to read as a 1 after flipping it on. This basically sets a theoretically threshold on how fast an entire chip can run. When you build a bigger chip, you're chaining more transistors and actually increase the total latency of the entire circuit. You end up with a less responsive circuit, you have to increase complexity to handle the timing issues that arise, and you also lower yields since bigger chip means less chips per wafer.

Also note, engineers tend to aim to shrink the gate length and width by ~70% every 2 years, which decreases the area of the gate by ~50%. Combine this with setting the electromagnetic field such that electron velocity holds constant, you can effectively double the speed of transistors. This is how Moore's Law is achieved. So 65nm * 0.7^6 =~ 7nm, meaning 65nm is at least 2^6=64X slower than 7nm.

It's commonly said the Xnm is not "real" anymore bc the design of the transistor has changed to FinFET and more recently, GAAFET, meaning the gate is no longer just a rectangle and so the performance isn't as easy to simply infer based on Xnm. The way we make them is by splitting lasers using crystals and mirrors until the light is only Xnm thin, then carve the circuitry on top of a silicon wafer

author: @kneekoo
comments: Russia has very talented software engineers. Hardware talent? It's hard to even guess. The way they manage stuff, their government, the corruption... all of these are probably a huge factor in why manufacturing lags behind others. This is just my uninformed perception as an outsider, but it really feels like Russia stifles its own innovation by trying to control way too much of its (private) industry. That said, rough times usually lead to innovation and who knows what kind of new CPUs we'll see coming from Russia, based on ARM or RISC-V. I hope Russia will get on the right path, but I'd also like to see it be more innovative - for good purposes that is.

author: @Warr1on
comments: Well, as a Russian i wouldn't say that we're lagging behind because of excessive control. It's likely on the contrary. The only reason MCST and Baikal currently exist is because of bailouts and the help of the government in terms of lawmaking policies and giving grants for development of the new stuff. And only after 2014, when Russia decided that we need to depend less on imports, only after our government started to support our microelectronics industry, we have started to see some new tech that can be considered relevant. Without control and support, there wouldn't even be any russian microelectronics at all, because no business would want to massively invest in something this risky and complicated and it's easier to just build an another shopping mall or re-brand imports as domestics and just start selling goods that are already manufactured.

author: @Warr1on
comments: Actually, re-branding imports as "domestics" and some shady companies exploiting loopholes in our laws of what can be considered domestic is a huge problem here. And that leads to the huge chunk of money being lost on this "domestic" manufacturing instead of going to the companies that actually develop and manufacture their tech in Russia. So I'd argue that there's a need in more strict control, especially now, when Russia desperately needs its own manufacturing and not just developments. This stuff won't just appear magically out of nowhere, the sad reality is that it needs to be controlled and supported by the government in order to even exist, you can't just let it go into a free-float and hope that the market would sort itself out.

author: @kneekoo
comments:
@@Warr1on By excessive control I meant measures to steer companies either in or away from the direction wanted by the government. And I might be wrong about this in Russia, but having experienced communism in my own country (Romania), I've seen how companies were "stimulated" to grow into the direction the Communist Party wanted, instead of allowing businesses to take part in the free market. Basically, politics steered and shaped the industry for some agenda.

Re-branding imports (finished products) as domestic products is fraud, which should be illegal everywhere. So this is not what I meant by control.

The industry needs more support indeed, but no steering. The market knows very well what it needs, the industry can easily recognize that, so the government should only support this and even make sure that (domestic) competition can exist, so that the need for talent can grow and innovation to occur as a result.

author: @WatcherSCP
comments: @@kneekoo State control in a communist country can be efficient and productive. A good example is China, whose economy has caught up with the United States. Communist Vietnam also makes a lot of progress in microelectronics and produces its own processors. At the same time, you can find dozens of free-market democracies on the map that don't produce any technology of their own at all. Open your eyes - democracy and free market is not the decisive factor. Of course, one can always remember the unsuccessful attempt to build socialism in Romania. But what is the practical meaning of this? You live in the past.

author: @kneekoo
comments:
â€‹@@WatcherSCP Living in the past? It looks like you're advertising communism or you completely missed my point about control done wrong. That's the problem, it's not about communism, but rather typical to communism. China made the same mistakes in the past but they learned. Russia (leadership) needs to learn too.

Free market actually means free - free to succeed and free to be mediocre or fail. If people expect their governments to manage businesses, that's a pretty broken system. Innovation needs to be stimulated and the government should get out of the way otherwise. Too many rules and regulations, or too much control hurt progress. Even the USA has too many stupid rules, regulations and laws that hinder the progress of Tesla and SpaceX. So again, my point was about excessive control.

author: @danielrodding8522
comments: No connection to international community, and on the hardware side permanent problems with in-country supply chains. Those "socialst" countries do not have a market-driven economy, but instead, material supply is planned for intervals of sometimes many years. Which makes complicated pushing forward innovation, especially it you do not know in advance what you'll need, and whether you get all that in time. Chip production is not only about theoretical know-how, but you also need a lot of lab and testing work to do, including running many test cycles. If you don't get enough supply for that, research and development are slowed down.

I anticipated  TMC chip sanctions and in my reading I came across 2 points not mentioned here that can soften the impact of chip sanctions.
 1) Russia has long declared chips Military Strategic items and has unregistered chips fabs inbedded in classified military/Aerospace institutions. Obviously what help they can offer the wider Russian Industry is unknown as they are classified but analysts have said the RU Gov has been preparing to upscale these production lines in anticipation of chip sanctions since 2014
2) The type of chips Russia is most dependent on. Russia is not a producer of many bleeding edge electronics, ie phones, graphics cards, supercomputers. Most of the chips required by Russian manufacturers are for heavy industry; Resource Extraction, Energy, Agri-tech, Heavy vehicles (Rail/Shipping). So that reduces the dependency on the highend chips TMC produces. (But the Russian Tech start up sector, like YANDEX, will suffer) 
YES Chip sanctions are going to impact, set back and force Russia to restratergise how it produces electronics.
But chips are probably the least of Russian Industries probs. It has suddenly found itself cut off from Western markets. Huge sections of its supply chains will need to be re-orintated or even re-constituted. Entire Industries will dissapear. Russia is going to change to a completely different economy focussing exclusively on trading with Asia, Sth America and Africa.

author: @iraqigeek8363
comments:
Amazing!
To give some sense of how old the 180nm node is, the original Willamette Pentium 4 released in 2000 was fabricated on a 180nm node. The 90nm node is what Intel used it to make the Dothan refresh of the Pentium-M in 2004, and the 65nm was used to make the Core 2 Duo in 2006!!!

AMD's dark days in 2012-2016, during the Piledriver/Steamroller/Excavator era (before Zen) Global Foundries was struggling to move beyond the 32/28nm nodes!

author: @raylopez99
comments: Nice geekwork.  From what I understand, making chips smaller (process node) only goes to the following issues:  less defects per wafer (smaller is better), different nodes and designs designs have better power consumption than others (90 nm was an energy hog), and the smaller the process node, the higher the volume (you can fit more chips on any given wafer).  Arguably for Soviet 'low volume' and "not sophisticated' designs, you can get away with 0.18 micron (180 nm) production.  But I'm glad the Russians are backwards.

author: @piotrcurious1131
comments:
@@raylopez99 Do not get fooled that russians are "backwards". Note that analysis focused on bleeding edge chips.
Strategic chips are sensors, transducers and memory chips. Also microcontrollers.
Smaller nodes get lower production yields. 
Also in case of nuclear war and widespread nuclear fallout, manufacture of small node chips will become progressivelly difficult. 
Soviets know well why going below 100um is not worth it, at least from military standpoint.
Last but not least rad-hard design is norm in Russia, also because of things like radioactive dust from their nuclear test sites and re-processing plants. Russians are used to protect their equipment. 
West is not. Very few people and factories protect their equipment, enjoying priviledge of living in non-radioactive world.
I used to live in a place with merely 5x of background radiation due to uranium mining and re-processing operations nearby. This causes many issues, even in electronics like switching inverters or transmitters, where transistors operate close to their breakdown voltages. 
It is all manageable, but comes with extra cost.

author: @geraldh.8047
comments:
Russian-Made Elbrus CPUs Fail Trials, 'A Completely Unacceptable Platform'

SberInfra, a technology arm of Sber, Russia's biggest bank, has evaluated the Russian-made MCST Elbrus-8C processors in multiple workloads, but the results were utterly disappointing and the processors failed the test. The testers cited "Insufficient memory, slow memory, few cores, low frequency. Functional requirements not been met at all" as key reasons for the failure. 

Toms Hardware, December 2021 ðŸ˜€

author: @PAPERMAsster
comments:
The conclusion may be correct, but it comes from the fact those chips use a completely different architecture from Intel/AMD x86 platform and design

Basically they mostly benefit from a multithreaded/distributed workload, while x86 (especially Intel) has a very high single core performance. 

What Sberbank did was just install java there and tried loading very heavy java server-applications which they claim are now running on 5 GHz Xeon-Platinum servers. Java just doesnâ€™t scale, and itâ€™s not that good at multi-core

If they were able to clusterize their processes and/or break into more efficient parts, the result would have been much better.

author: @geraldh.8047
comments: @@PAPERMAsster The problem is that unless you are doing video encoding or crypto mining, most processes are really hard to properly parallelize... Also I doubt they can compete even for multithreaded things. And they complained about general things this server did not have like remote management.

author: @vitalegvitalegov
comments: @@PAPERMAsster several weeks ago one curious Russian developer published the article (at Habr) on trying to reach top performance with Elbrus. He made lots of optimizations and came very close to Intel's performance. But the conclusion was, it is too labour-prone, in many cases it won't pay for itself.

The cost of production in China is magnitudes lower than in the USA, and say Taiwan becomes part of Mainland China again (through force or otherwise), TSMC's factories in Japan and the USA are going to be significantly more expensive than anything China is producing. 

It's like a giant deadly game of chess unfolding in front of us and i'm both scared and fascinated.

author: @raylopez99
comments:
Liver busters, good one.  I've heard back in the day and even now, TSMC does the Asian thing and pay a huge bonus at the end of the year, that way they can fire you one day before the bonus and not have to pay.  Also keeps people from jumping ship until at least they've put in a year's time.  The beneficiary is, for now, the consumer, until such time TSMC gets monopoly pricing power, which arguably their customers have but not yet TSMC.  

I think the shift towards Windows 11 by 2024 will increase PC sales from the current 300M units a year to something higher.  But I don't think there's that much money in chips, just do the math:  300M chips a year * $450 a chip (best guess for the avg price of a retail processor chip) = $135B USD of revenue.  That's peanuts (Volkswagen auto group alone makes about $250B a year).  Triple this number for all other chips and that's still only about $400B a year.  At the end of the day, chips are great for geeks but the real money is still being a gatekeeper (doctor, lawyer, businessman who buys low and sells high).

author: @profdc9501
comments: The progress in microfabrication is amazing, but it seems like mitigating the risks of supply problems has still been hardly considered, and the giant fabrication facilities may ultimately fail because there are simply so much that can go wrong with them.  The titanic costs and almost incomprehensible complexity of these processes seems like it could become easily unmanageable at some point in the near future given hte endless resources that must be obtained, wafers, photoresists, specialty chemicals for layer deposition, metal deposition, enormous amounts of water, solvents, acids, and bases for cleaning and stripping, the dependence on many different types of photolithography processes to complete a wafer,  ion implanation and annealing, among the countless other equipment and supplies.   Technology is more fragile than ever and the semiconductor supply chain problems may be just a symptom that this complexity becoming too much to manage.

author: @michaelharrison1093
comments:
They have heavily invested into GaN on Si technology that is used in power electronics applications (e.g. phone chargers, computer power supplies, & EV).  TSMC have developed what is called a Schottky Gate, Enhancement Mode, High Electron Mobility Transistor (HEMT) technology.  They are not alone in regards to GaN HEMT technology but unique in their business model.   TSMC realized that they didn't want to get involved in anything more than the semiconductor fab side of this emerging industry so they offer their GaN fab capabilities to a number of independent "fabless" companies who are looking  after all other parts of the business. 

These fabless GaN companies include Navitas and GaN Systems as well as STMicroelectronics - however STM have also invested directly based on their acquisition of Exagan.

author: @benjaminlynch9958
comments:
Another awesome video.

One thing Iâ€™ve been wondering about is what happens to fabs when the leading edge customer move on to the next node? Presumably TSMC (and Samsung/Intel/Global Foundries) built huge capacity at 12/16/28nm. But those nodes are no longer good enough for products that need the leading edge. Thereâ€™s always stuff that doesnâ€™t need leading edge, but I always assumed that all those products were being made on old mature nodes where it would be cost prohibitive (with little economic benefit) to transition to newer process nodes. Also, what is the global demand situation for all those use cases beyond the leading edge? It seems like there would have to be pretty significant demand growth to absorb the entire manufacturing capacity of a new process node every every 2-3 years. We know the demand is there for leading edge, but what about older nodes. Specifically, as TSMC transitions to 3nm (primarily Apple to start) and more customers like AMD & nVidia move more production to 5nm, what happens to all of TSMCâ€™s 7nm capacity if itâ€™s no longer being used for GPUâ€™s and desktop/laptop CPUâ€™s? Whoâ€™s taking all that capacity?

author: @villageidiot8194
comments: I think its going to be used in chips for cars, for the infotainment system, dishwashers, TVs, and other appliances

author: @excitedbox5705
comments:
They market those nodes to other customers. Apple got 5nm first but the year after AMD and Nvidia will use that node. Also makes sense because mobile chips are smaller and the yield for the much larger GPU and CPU chips will be better after the node is more mature. Flaws are usually calculated on a per area basis which is also why AMD chiplets gave them such an advantage, since a smaller chip has less chance of failure and if something goes wrong it is less to throw away.

Older nodes are still useful for other chips though. Lots of analog and mixed signal ICs are made on larger nodes because you would burn through the traces with so much current otherwise. Keysight oscilloscope ASICs for example were being made on nodes over 100nm (130nm in the 4th gen Infiniivision) but now went with a 65nm node recently. The lower cost of using an ASIC also allows them to use the same chip in many product lines. You can buy a $1000 scope with the same chip as their $50,000 or $1 million scopes. The higher tier ones use multiple chips together, while the base models share 1 chip for multiple channels.

author: @Fiercesoulking
comments: Like in the videos said a lot of nodes get upgraded those who weren't end up the with the stuff said from @Village also there are other manufactures who can't under 20 nm those are specialist in doing chips for other uses then computer. Interesting is when we really hit the physical limits in a few years other companies then have a chance to catch up to ASML/TSMC while this will take many years it will push the prices down.

author: @lubricustheslippery5028
comments: The fabs usually continue to produce chips for other customers/purposes. There is more integrated circuits in your computer than the CPU and GPU. And there is circuits in more and more other places to.

author: @RobBCactive
comments:
Also process improvements like recent 6nm can be viable in a nominally 7nm fab extending its prime economic life.
As costs for new processes rise, the chiplet/tile approach allowing a mix of small dies using different processes in the same package  makes sense.

author: @SpielbaerLP
comments:
Investors and tech experts 2005: Microsoft is game over! Old company based on old products.
Investors and tech experts 2008: AMD is game over, their technology can't hold up against competitors.
Investors and tech experts 2021: Intel is game over, their technology can't hold up against competitors.
I am rather buying Intel which is priced rather cheap compared to those other stocks mentioned. If one believes the Semi Cycle is not going to end here then Intel will just benefit especially when switching their model to foundry for Amazon, QCOM and co. And should China indeed take Taiwan "home" the cards suddenly change all over.

author: @G3r4pro
comments: One concern for me is that i fear intel might turn into an IBM.... I'm still buying a little bit though

author: @SpielbaerLP
comments: @@G3r4pro At the current valuation intel is actually priced just as cheap. It's as if the market believes the company goes out of business. That is generally a good time to buy more especially once you realize that their focus on the foundry business is a clever long term strategic idea. Plus there is a nice dividend and buybacks all more than well covered by earnings. Is there risks involved? Sure. Is it all priced in yet? Looks quite like it. Would you rather buy much higher valued companies that may drop the ball as well at some point and can fall huge when it happens? That's the question.

author: @SpielbaerLP
comments: @Thieve the world, dispense only the good In the end, it all depends on your time horizon. Ten years ago everyone was declaring AMD as being dead: Bad tech, years to catch up, bad server chips, etc. Things will turn the other way eventually especially with a company as large as intel with huge amounts of cash on hand and big cash flows still coming in. I really do not care so much about what the perception is right now because ten years down the road, you might think i am crazy for having bought AMD or TSMC here ^^

author: @SpielbaerLP
comments: @Thieve the world, dispense only the good I tend to agree on certain points. However, the risk reward is still better at Intel right now ;) Time will tell if the horror scenario you are painting is completely correct.

author: @pizzadoe7922
comments:
Only those who aren't in the GPU market will find Nvidia's order cancellation surprising. I have been saying for months, that Nvidia is going to get hit hard because ETH 2.0 merge is coming this year. Nvidia is able to price at a premium because their GPUs are excellent crypto miners. It is not a reflection of the gaming market. As more crypto moves to PoS, Nvidia GPUs are going to hammer further. It is expensive and runs hot. AMD is cheaper and does just as well for your average gamer.

Nvidia is a great company but its P/E is driven by investors misinformed about the GPU market.

author: @MarkBanks77
comments: Nvidia doesn't want their GPU's used for crypto, hence the hash rate limiters they added to all GeForce cards. Cover your short position soon.

author: @fauxbro1983
comments: @@MarkBanks77 Nvidia wants to sell thier GPUs to any buyers. What you smoking

author: @MarkBanks77
comments: @@fauxbro1983 Nvidia sells all its video cards regardless. Jensen Huang said he would prefer them in the hands of gamers rather than mining crypto in a warehouse, hence the hash rate limiters.

author: @pizzadoe7922
comments:
@@MarkBanks77 Oh Nvidia does too. They even sold their earliest batches of Ampere cards directly to GPU miners.

They only started with the LHR version because they got caught selling to miners and received backlash from gamers. Miners will pay exorbitant prices to get GPU because ETH mining has been very profitable - especially when you stake ETH after the merge and earn passive income. Nvida knows this and it is no coincidence that the most expensive card 3090 didn't have an LHR lock.

Without a doubt, Nvidia's past sales were inflated because the ETH price exploded. That is why scalpers had their heyday with pricing Nividia GPU at exorbitant prices on eBay. They weren't targeting gamers at those prices; they were chasing after miners. 

There is no coincidence that Nvidia GPU had a larger shortage than AMD's GPU, despite AMD being cheaper and equally competent in gaming. 

Now miners are dumping their cards before the merge is complete. Gamers can buy used cards from miners directly - taking new sales away from Nvidia. 

When investors realize how much Nvidia's revenue came from miners, Nvidia's stock price is set for a correction.

author: @ciscoterres717
comments: Taiwan has historically had a "wild wild west" policy over pollution standards, for the sake of growth. For example - battery manufacturers dumping raw battery acid straight to the ocean, and untreated solid human waste being dumped into rivers and the ocean. Most (probably all) streams and rivers in Taiwan are dangerously polluted, with high levels of lead and hepatitis and plastics and who knows what else. Its estimated that over 90% of Taiwanese have been infected with hepatitis. Most homes in Taiwan have no sanitation system, so waste is dumped straight to rivers or the ocean. Burning of huge mounds of waste is the main method that Taiwan is using to dispose of waste. Of course, the air quality is really bad because of it. Taiwan is trying to work towards improving their pollution and waste regulations, but its been slow going. Growth and $$$ is always #1.

author: @pweddy1
comments:
When it comes to TSMC's impact on the world economy it's not about Ryzen or x86s.

Most cars don't use x86s but they do use DSPs and microcontrollers that are built by companies using TSMC.  

China taking over TSMC means manufactures of everything from cars to microwaves have to redesign there entire product lines around a different set of chips.  Most of these are microcontrollers and are small and special purpose.  They can't use a i3 to replace the parts being manufactured at TSMC and Intel isn't ready to be a 3rd party chip fab for 1/2 the planet.

There are no x86s in anything safety critical in the US military.  But there are Xilinx FPGAs, DSP from various manufacturers and microcontrollers.  Some of the latest military tech is guaranteed to be using a chip supplier that uses TSMC's fabs.

The reason the US can't sit on there hands if China makes a move on Taiwan is the supply chain for the US military.

I'm about 35 minutes in so forgive me if what I'm about to say is already covered, but in reference to Tom's question about China's willingness to help Russia i'll say this. As a result of the sanctions placed in Russia  by the west more specifically the European Union, Russia needed to reroute it's oil supply, to do this they turned to China and India and gave them oil at a relatively cheap price around 60 dollars per barrel, so in theory this would benefit Chinese manufacturing because the cost of energy would be cheaper.
However, the real reason why China would assist Russia is because of the Taiwan issue, the Chinese has always maintained the stance that Taiwan is a part of China, and with the recent events of Nancy Pelosi visiting Taiwan and doing all but recognizing it as it's own independent country, the Chinese relationship with the west isn't particularly the strongest as well. It's the old adage of 'the enemy of my enemy is my friend'.

Now my own personal opinion is that Russia's tech sector would be fine one way or another, people say Russia is just a gas station but without that gas no major industry stays running so it's very simplistic to judge Russia's economy on just the GDP alone without context.

author: @PhazerTech
comments:
Great video, thanks Tom.  Something you should have mentioned when it comes to AMD vs Nvidia in software and AI computing:  AMD has launched 'GPUFORT' which is an open source attempt against CUDA.  AMD's hardware is certainly capable of doing these tasks.  When it comes to creation software, hardware support has been added to UE5 and Blender for recent gen AMD GPUs.  They're not as fast the RTX 3000 series, but they give very usable performance.  This is probably because the software is still new and hasn't had time to be optimized yet.
When it comes to scientific computing and AI, the problem is that CUDA is proprietary and that's what most of the software has been written for.  But AMD has created the open source solution GPUFORT as an alternative.  Competition is always a good thing, and AMD realizes they need to compete in these markets as well.  Let's hope more developer take advantage of it, the fact it's open source sounds promising.

comments: @@codycast Objectively, Historically...absolutely not.  Look at AMD then when they owned GF, look at Intel now.  Countless analysis exists on why Vertical Integration in the chip industry is problematic beyond 10nm.

author: @eclipsegst9419
comments: @@VRforAllIntel may have had a rough patch, but that doesn't prove that owning your fabs is bad. When Intel had its issues with 14nm, they were the undisputed leader. There was no other process on the globe that was better for them to use instead. now, 3 years later, when they finally got things fixed, yes, they had fallen behind. But they did what they had to do, and now they are heading back for the top. And, they aren't just making their own things, they are going into the foundry buisness in general. Having your own stuff is always better in the long run. AMD jumping ship to TSMC looked great at the time. Looks great right now. But how will it look if the Chinese take over? They will be stuck in a boat without a paddle. So will Apple. And who will they have to come begging to? Samsung... and.... Intel.

author: @VRforAll
comments: @@eclipsegst9419 Yes the dwindling sources of leading edge fabs is a problem.  Intel themselves has tried to diversify their fabs to other clients and are actively pursuing chip designs on TSMC.  These facts alone underscores the fallacy of Vertical chip manufacturing in modern times.  In the past Yes absolutely, Intel dominated for decades with their all in-house designs fully optimized from top to bottom.   This is precisely the cause of their current predicament.   Intel's monoculture optimized designs are incompatible with the rest of the industry.  3rd party clients are leary in investing designs becoming beholden to Intel only(single source).  Apple is currently transitioning from Intel, a chip partner since 2006.  Intels ongoing fab issues have been ongoing for over a decade.  Not saying it's game over for Intel, but times have changed.  Intel is no longer the only choice for cloud infrastructure,  contractual agreements are expiring and the move to more efficient designs away from Intel are becoming the norm.  Intel no longer has the fab advantage nor do they have Win/Intel duopoly nor do they have the x86 monopoly on server and are currently losing Apple.   Many would conclude that Intel's reliance on their all in-house Vertical chip designs as the primary cause of their current predicament.  Intel has known this for years and was slow to pivot.  Not out per se...but the worst is yet to come for Intel.

author: @korana6308
comments:
Hi Tom, as a long time channel subscriber and someone who follows Russian micro electronics quite well, I would like to clarify a few things ... Boy, there were alot of misconception and misunderstanding in this video about Russian semi conductor industry and about Russia in general, but for the sake of it, let's just try keep it at microelectronics... 

Currently Russia is capable of producing 65nm at Mikron fabs in Zelenograd near Moscow, and is working towards a 45nm node, however for the types of products that they are producing, they don't need the most advanced stuff, and many people are missing that point. You need a cutting edge node mainly for the consumer sector to survive in a capitalistic consumer market ...but in fact for the military it's quite the opposite, as you would rather have a more reliable tech node (that consumes more power ,yet is powerful enough for it's intended operation) but is less so prone to damage or electromagnetic manipulations/ interference, and Russia fully produces those types of products - chips and there are no shortages on anything that would make the production of those types of chips decline.

Also it is a huge understatement to say that Russia had no expertise back in the Soviet era or now ,or that it didn't produce anything technologically worthwhile back in the Soviet era as that is a complete lie. The exponential growth of semiconductor industry happened exactly in the 90s with PCs ,Mobile Phones and consoles... and Soviet Union would have had the same consumer products or even better ones than Intel , if not for it's dissolution (i.e Russia already had the most successful gaming consoles like tetris, or "volk i yaica" from electroniks and it's clones...) Most of the Soviet technology is just simply unknown to the west (Just like how now you almost don't know anything about China, while they are making huge leaps in tech. development every year). For example the most famous Soviet Autonomous Space Shuttle program Buran , which have  had even a new largest plane in the world developed specifically just for it (An 225) , which was capable of autonomous landing a space shuttle with it's Soviet era Computers back in the 80s... In fact USSR had lots of technological advancements most of which were hidden behind it's military and space tech, which was even greater than it's western counterparts (same for the west btw, internet developed out of the military tech, same now for Russia btw too) ... Most of it ,by the way, was stolen by the Americans , and not vice versa as your video would have suggested, like the shuttle program - Buran, or the Yak 141 (vertical take off jet plane) like the F35 etc... 

To give you an example of one of those people standing behind those soviet era CPU developments is - Boris Babayan which was later hired by Intel , as he and his team had greatly helped Intel with their CPUs development and encryptions... So there would have been an even better CPU, if all of those smart Soviet people were put to good use in the 90s , and if the Soviet Union didn't collapse ...and there would have been some great consumer CPUs for sure... But... it is what it is. The point is that ,Russia has had , back in the Soviet days ,and still has the expertise and institutes ,and more importantly people , to develop and produce high tech semiconductor products and chips , and even nodes, which for some reason western people always underestimate...

One of those Russian processors that Boris Babayan had also worked on during his days was the Elbrus CPUs (and it's micro architecture)... which is another topic that hasn't been talked about much in the west at all, and that CPU actually greatly improves with each generation , as it roughly doubles it's performance with each gen... They are however ofcourse not licensed to have a x86 architecture, so they are developed mainly for the Linux based systems and for specific data computation and analyzing tasks... However their integrated transcoder is capable of running a x86 just fine ( with some loss in perf. for transcoding ofcourse). As a VLIW architecture it was developed for the different task in mind, and in those specific tasks it is already faster than Intel. However there's this youtube channel called" Elbrus PC Play " as those enthusiast guys (streams are in Russian) have already been running it on Windows 10 on an old (10 year old) Elbrus PC with Radeon R9 370 4GB Graphics. ( as Russian Elbrus only has an integrated 2D Graphics , so they need an AMD GPU to play games)... And modern games actually already ran at playable FPS (even with 30% to 60% loss of perf. due to transcode decryption, which in theory could be improved). However with it's newer version of Elbrus 16C and a modern GPU I would expect that modern games would be able to run at 30 - 60 fps. no problem (with potentially natively programmed games, i.e. in a console scenario, they will get even more FPS than intel or AMD... but that scenario (of a console) is extremely unlikely to occur) . The beauty is ofcouse is that everything was designed and developed in Russia and is going to come to the consumer market too eventually (technically it is already) ... yet their next gen Elbrus 32C will be even better and could in theory become a competitor to Intel and AMD... at least in the Russian and CIS + allies market in theory... 300+ mil people ). (There are also other Russian CPUs like Baikal, but they all have ARM cores in them , only Elbrus has a fully unique Russian core.)

And the caveat is ofcourse is that those chips manufacturing is outsourced to the TSMC's fab at Taiwain as it is on a 14nm node. And also the CPU is quite expensive with a 16C expected to be up to $10 grand USD, as it's main purpose is for the governmental and scientific work and it is not produced in large quantities yet . But it is one of the examples of the Russian technological semiconductor designs development, which was unfairly skimped on, to say the least, in this video.

Thanks.

author: @DragonBitesTail
comments:
@@shepardpolska Catching up is what you have to do when you are behind in something you're competing at.  How you go about catching up is what people having their work copied may have a problem with.  
And, no licensing is the legal means by which you are granted rights to some aspect of a technology by the copyright holder. It's not stealing.

An example of stealing very typical in the Chinese market is to reverse engineer a product, create a copy, then label it as the same product and sell it in China.  Sometimes they call it something else. 

None of the money made from that knockoff goes back to the original company who holds the copyright.

author: @Avantime
comments:
@@UhOhUmm And those non-Chinese suppliers won't have any access to the Chinese market, which is the world's biggest consumer market for electronics. China is by far the lowest price producer simply because they produce for everyone plus themselves, and for commodity products you require extreme economies of scale.

Anyway no non-Chinese supplier will be able to scale quickly, because production equipment manufacturers (don't forget a lot of production equipment are also made in China) will themselves face a supply crunch. There's always a big Chinese player from mining to downstream value-added processes, if you remove some, prices skyrocket. If you remove all of them, the supply chain grinds to a halt.

In the long run, yes the West could get a non-Chinese supply chain going. But forget about $1,000 iPhones, they'll be more like $2,000. Electronics will cease become cheap - maybe that's a good thing, but this will push inflation upward, and lower peoples' living standards.

author: @poitiers2853
comments: @@tringuyen7519 Actually, tundra is very nutrient-rich soil.  Problem is those nutrients are frozen.  Plenty of tundra farmers in Alaska and Canada.  Mostly small family farms growing very high quality organic vegetables and even grains.  First, find an area of tundra that has access to a water source.  Second, the insulation cap needs to be removed to expose the frozen soil so that sunlight can access and thaw it enough to till.  That means first removing the shrub and brush covering the soil, allow the Sun to thaw the top soil, then it will be ready for tilling.  Then add mulched tundra plants, compost, and other natural fertilizer such as manure or fish.  After the fields are amended with compost, the fields need to be reshaped into long rows of raised soil beds.  This is a two year process.  For shorter Sun/growing seasons, plastic greenhouse sheeting can be used over crops since the soil is already prepared.

author: @cassius_eu5970
comments:
Taiwan is a multi-faceted issue but there are two main reasons for why the PRC wants to reunify with Taiwan. 

First, every Chinese knows the century of humiliation that China suffered from the Opium War to 1949. Nearly all the historical vestiges of this century of humiliation have been removed or resolved, including Hong Kong and Macau.

Only one remains: Taiwan. It was Chinese territory until China was forced to hand it to Japan after the defeat in the Sino-Japanese War of 1894-1895. The Chinese have been disappointed by the US several times on Taiwan. At the end of World War I, when China thought it had worked with the US, it initially received assurance from the US and the British that Taiwan would be returned to China at the Versailles Peace Conference. The Chinese were told that the territories would be restored to the young republic, as a reward for the efforts of the nearly 100,000 Chinese workers who had been sent to the front in Europe to assist the British and French. But the territories were awarded instead to Japan. The Americans and British turned out to have made simultaneous secret agreements with both China and Japan, and China felt enormously deceived by that.

This history has taught the Chinese not to accept American assurances. Any move by the US to support, directly or indirectly, the secession of Taiwan from China brings back this historical memory. It provokes a strong, powerful, and virulent national reaction, which boxes in any Chinese leader who may be trying to look for room to manoeuvre. And the US cannot claim that it doesnâ€™t understand the significance of Taiwan. It was clearly the hottest issue to resolve when Nixon and Kissinger began the process of reconciliation with China. Many clear understandings were reached between America and China. The most explicit understanding reached was that Taiwan and China belonged to one country, and that the government of the PRC is the legitimate government of that country.

Second, there are also the strategic considerations: Taiwan blockaded the PRC for 30+ years under ROC port closure policy (with US assent). There were over 140 incidents where Taiwan was threatening and intercepting trade vessels, including international ones, right off the PRC coast and within the PRC's national waters. The only reason why Taiwan isn't doing that anymore is because the PRC is far stronger now. But Taiwan has proven to be too much of a security liability (especially as a US asset) for the PRC to ignore.

Tom, you managed to fundamentally misunderstand what TSMC means when they say a particular node provides a particular percentage performance improvement.
They are *not* talking about performance per die size, they are talking about performance for a specific architecture, or performance per transistor.

author: @MooresLawIsDead

author: @nathangamble125
comments:
â€‹@@MooresLawIsDead TSMC get these numbers by building an ARM-based test chip on two different nodes, and testing what clock speeds the chip can run at at a fixed power usage. Because the chips are built on different nodes, their sizes will be different, i.e. TSMC's numbers are per-transistor, or per-architectural-unit, not per-die-size. Performance per die size isn't necessarily correlated with performance per transistor when you're comparing GPUs with wildly different architectures and transistor counts.

Of course, you will gain performance whether you're using the die shrink to run at higher clock speeds on a smaller die, or to add more transistors to end up with a die around the same size, but the scaling is not the same (especially when you're comparing different architectures), so it's not a perfect correlation.

Anandtech has an article on this (Early TSMC 5mn test chip yields 80%) which explains how TSMC gets these numbers, including information about the test chip which they use.

The percentage performance differences end up somewhat similar whether you base the calculation on die size or transistor count, because increasing the number of transistors (for a given architecture at a given clock frequency) also increases performance and power usage, but you'd get more accurate results if you used the numbers to mean what they actually mean, not something vaguely similar. You used a lazy method to calculate something that resembles the real value. You could argue that it works well enough for the purposes of this video, but it's not as reliable as doing the calculation properly.

To get more accurate numbers you should be comparing GPUs with (at least approximately) the same number of CUDA cores, TMUs and ROPs; not GPUs with the same die size, because power scaling with die size/transistor count is not linear. For example you could compare the GTX 980 to the GTX 1070 Max-Q - both have 2048 CUDA cores, 128 TMUs and 64 ROPs, and their clock speeds are relatively close, so manual adjustment wouldn't introduce a huge amount of error. Either that, or you should be accounting for the non-linear power scaling with die size in your calculation.

For clarity, I mostly don't disagree with your conclusions in this video, but I disagree with your method.

author: @nathangamble125
comments:
@@MooresLawIsDead Your calculation assumes:
1. That power scaling with transistor count/die area (at a given clock speed) is linear. It isn't. In most cases power usage is approximately proportional to the _square root_ of die size, not directly propotional.
2. That every node has approximately the same ratio between power savings and scale factor (i.e. perfect Dennard scaling). This hasn't been true since around 2006.

author: @DGao-zz5vq
comments:
CUDA core is Nvidiaâ€™s marketing name for its FP32 unit. If you put the block diagrams of Ampere and Turing next to each other, youâ€™ll see what was going on.

A Turing Stream Multiprocessor (SM) is made up of 4 partitions, each containing - among other things - 16 FP32 units (CUDA cores) and 16 INT32 units. Therefore a Turing SM contains 64 FP32-capable units, hence 64 CUDA/SM.

For the most part an Ampere SM has a similar arrangement. However, the INT32 units from Turing have been converted into INT32 / FP32 combo units. An Ampere SM contains 128 FP32-capable units, 64 of them dedicated to FP32, the other 64 are combo units.

Every clock cycle, the INT32 / FP32 combo data path of an Ampere partition can process either 16 INT32 ops *or* 16 FP32 ops. So while in a pure FP32 workload the combo units deliver the same amount of throughput as the dedicated FP32 units, in a more realistic workload the combo units are weaker - every clock cycle they spend processing INT32 ops is one they are not processing FP32 ops. This is why it appeared that Ampereâ€™s per CUDA performance regressed from where Turing was.

The Ampere leaks assumed that Nvidia would market only the dedicated FP32 units as CUDA cores, and the CUDA core count would be calculated the same way as Turing, i.e. 64*SM count = CUDA count.
Instead Nvidia decided to count combo units as full CUDA cores, and Ampere cardsâ€™ CUDA count became (64+64)*SM count = CUDA count.
Tomâ€™s Ampere information wasnâ€™t wrong, itâ€™s just Nvidia choosing to market it differently.

author: @Gindi4711
comments:
Your math is giving me headaches.

Here is how it works (example N7 vs. N5):

TSMC gives these numbers:
-30% Power usage
OR
+15% Performance (clock speeds)
AND
1.6x density (1.8x for logic, 1.3x for SRAM, 1.2x for analog but lets say 1.6x to make it simple)

Lets say you have a chip in N7 with: 100FP32*1GHz = 100GFlop, 100W and 100mmÂ²

What this means is that by shrinking this chip you either get:
a) 100GFlop, 100-30% = 70W and 100/1.6=62.5mmÂ²
So same clock speeds, same performance, just a smaller chip that uses less energy.

Or you pump up clock speeds for same power consumption:
b) 100 FP32 * 1,15GHz = 115GFlop, 100W, 62.5mmÂ²

Note: This does not mean that N5 support 15% higher maximum clock speeds (for example Zen3 with single core boost of 5GHz), but only that you can get 15% somewhere in the middle of the frequency curve.

What GPU vendors usually do is use option a, but increase chip size to be at the same density again which linearly increases (theoretical) performance AND power consumption:
c) 1600*1GHz = 160GFlop, 70*1.6=112W, 100mmÂ²

Notice that the performance increase of 1.6x is a lot higher than the stated 1.15x (even if you reduce clocks to match 100W).


So lets do the calculation again focusing only on power consumption (assuming TSMC 10FF is equal to 10LPP):
8LPP vs. N7P = 0.66x (8LPP => 10LPP = 1.1x, 10FF vs. N7P is about 0.6x)
N7P vs. N5P = 0.7x
N5P vs. N4P = 0.9x

So in total 0.416x or 2.4x performance/W if at the same clockspeeds

From kopite7kimi we already know AD102 is 70-80B billion transistors. Subtract 4B for 86MB additional SRAM (L2) and we are down to 66B-76B. So lets say 71B. This is about 2.5x of GA102 which means 2.5x performance.

Let say a 3090 Ti is 450W and 1.1x performance over a 3090 (which was the reference for previous performance claims):
So this means 2.5 * 1.1 = 2.65x performance at 450 * 2.5/2.4 = 470W
If we go from 470W to 600W (1.28x) I think we can expect something like 10% higher clock speeds for 28% more power so 2.65 * 1.1 = 2.9x performance

Please keep in mind that this is a rough calculation not considering any architecture changes, different scaling behaviour of some GPU parts (IO and GDDR6x interface do not need to be scaled 2.5x, ROPs/TMUs not so much if the card is used at higher resolutions, on the other hand RT parts or L2 control logic might see more than 2.5x scaling etc.)

author: @MooresLawIsDead
comments:
You are falling into the same trap people who overhyped RDNA 2 fell into.  Navi 21 has 26.8 Million Transistors and Navi 10 has 10.3 Million Transistors.  Is Navi 21 2.6x the performance of Navi 10 bud?  NO.  In fact, the 6900 XT needs 33% more energy just to get to a 2.05x performance boost over the 5700 XT.  Even if you remove the space occupied by the Infinity Cache, it still doesn't make up for the fact that you need over 2.1x the transistors AND higher clocks to get to 2.05x performance.

RDNA 2 had higher clocks than RDNA 1, 2.6x the transistors, and a groundbreaking architecture...but it didn't perfectly scale with transistors like you claim is so easy.  Real life is not theoretical math - the world isn't perfect.

I'll keep going since this is funny to me, here's an Nvidia example: The Titan RTX has 18.6 Million Transistors (remember this is the ACTUAL full TU102 that is a full 11% stronger than the 2080 Ti), and the 450w 3090 Ti (actual full GA102 die) has 28.3 Million Transistors.  So that's a 52% increase in transistors for typically 43-50% more performance...and they had to increase power consumption by an incredible 60% to even achieve that!!!  Go ahead and compare the 2080 Ti to the 3090 if you bloody want to instead - in that case it's 46% more performance with a 40% increase in power consumption despite 52% more transistors in the full dies.

So let's now recap what you are claiming shall we?  You are now you're going to tell me, that Nvidia is going to somehow linearly scale performance with transistors while "only" increasing power by 33%?   If they do so, it's an incredible accomplishment, not something we should all just blindly accept that they can "just do".  They failed at it before despite having far superior node upgrades to work with in the past.

author: @Gindi4711
comments:
â€‹@@MooresLawIsDead The whole discussion comes down to the question how "3x performance" is defined:
a) All the other leakers (and also me in my calculations) are talking about performance of the GPU
b) You are talking about gaming fps.

But gaming fps do not scale linearly with GPU performance. With the current gen using high end CPU + GPU fps scale about 75% with GPU performance so you have to increase GPU performance by 20% to get 15% more fps.

At lower resolutions scaling is even worse and it shifts more towards CPU and fixed delays. This will also happen with the next gen at Native 4K without RT.
My expection is that fps scaling on the next generation will be around 50-60% at Native 4K.

So the 2.9x performance in my calcuation will lead to 80% higher framerates.

Or in other words: Going from a 3090 to AD102 in 4K will be like going from a 3060 to a 3090 Ti in 1080p
At more GPU intensive setting like 8K or 4K + RT it will be higher.


For your examples:
5700XT vs. 6900XT:
This comparision is flawed because:
.) 6 billion (128MB*8Bits*6Transistor/Bit) transistors have been used on the 128MB of SRAM to compensate not scaling memory interface
.) TDP did not scale

AMD achieved 2x gaming fps (in 4K) which translates to around 2.5x GPU performance.
They did that 2x transistors (if you subtract the 128MB SRAM)
And they did that without increasing TDP 2x even when considering the 10% lower power consumption they got from going N7 => N7P
This was possible because there were still some serious issues in RDNA1 that seems to got at least partially solved in RDNA2

For Titan RTX vs. 3090:
.) 3090 got 1.7x GPU performance (1 Ampere SM equals 1.5 Turing SMs see 3070 vs. 2080 Ti caused by 64 active FP vs. 96 active FP with the other 32 doing INT)
.) TDP was scaled 1.25x so 1.36x reduction (which sounds reasonable going from a refined 16nm process to a refined 10nm process (sorry dont have exact numbers what it should be).
.) The 1.7x performance translate to 48% fps assuming 75% scaling again

author: @phunkscunk6872
comments:
You talk out of both sides of your mouth, when it comes to AMD you have astronomical predictions and defy this reasoning.  You have all this rationale, crumbled up and tossed aside for RDNA 3.  Stacking or chiplets, can really be beneficial in many ways for AMD but it is not magic. Monolithic chips are difficult because of yields, there is always a percentage of imperfections. This is why there are cut down chips, to make use of an imperfect chips.  A percentage of the chips are sold as cut down variants, it is not ideal but it mostly an issue of cost, capacity, how many full flat usable chips per wafer.  Chiplets are great for many reasons, they can help to get the most out of a to to wafer.  More chips per wafer, you should be able to buy/use less silicon and therefore  make more money.  Essentially, not having to so many cut down chips, or lower tier products made up from larger chips with wasted silicon that is fused off.
It is economic and sensible but not magical.

Everything you say about Nvidias Ada all must apply to AMD RDNA3 as well.
people forget somehow that you are still working within the boundaries, a finite power envelope and still within the constraints of the process nodes capabilities.   Nvidia monolithic designs are not just one type of transistor but rather they make use of a variety of transistors, not one type for one area but each segment contains a combo.  They utilize fast, high performance, and low power throughout the chip

author: @OneAngrehCat
comments:
This is a very interesting point you raise at the end.

What amazes me in the current battle isn't the current or upcoming gens, but their sequel. With RDNA2 x Ampere, we had near performance equality. With RDNA3 x Lovelace, we will probably have AMD take the lead by a small margin, but Nvidia can still save the furniture by holding on to a few cards. Even if say only the 4060 or 4070 competes or is better than the 7600 or 7700, Nvidia will still not be too damaged.

But what after? Nvidia is already being cornered into making absurd power consumptions to even hold its ground. It's sacrificing good engineering (I.E knowing your limits/doing what's sensible) to keep at least a hand on the throne. RDNA 1 let Nvidia walk away laughing from a non-fight. RDNA 2 had them take things seriously. RDNA 3 is already forcing them to do absurdities just to keep their head above the water.

If RDNA4 brings in even just 50% performance increase, a year or so after RDNA3, what is Nvidia going to do? Pump out a 750W card? I'm seeing the walls shrink around them.

With Intel, AMD is at this point skinning an oversized, terribly managed hippo of a company. But Nvidia isn't Intel. They did not start hacking away at their own competence in the name of stocks or client deals. Nvidia took the place of richest company in tech from Intel precisely because it didn't stray from the product growth. They're not going to bumble around and just accept AMD to dice them like it's been doing to Intel. This competition is not going to simply be AMD ruling it all forever. The only question is, when will Nvidia be able to start doing the same effort AMD did? Switching from their old CPUs to Ryzen cost a lot of time and money. Vega to RDNA did the same. Now the dividends have started paying and they're gonna pay a lot more yet.

When will Nvidia sacrifice the same large amount of time and money to rethink their entire architecture? I think that's the most important question. I doubt that they can avoid doing what AMD did around the time of the 400-500-5000 series.

author: @yungnachty4474
comments:
Something I feel could really affect AMD's ability to gain market share at the high end in another few years is that GPUs are getting powerful at a rate that far exceeds any improvement in monitor tech. The first 4K 144hz monitors were announced in CES(January) of 2016....that is 6 years ago? And still the fastest/most demanding monitors on the market are 4K 144hz. Sure these things have dropped from 2000+ to like 1000 USD, but they also don't include the same specs as those first 4K 144hz like HDR 1000. So effectively, monitors haven't improved that much in terms of 4K panels. The only improvements we have gotten really are 240hz 1440P panels, by way of newer display port standards. 

There are 1440P 32:9 monitors(3000USD+  & plagued with QA problems), running 240hz...but that is still only slightly more than 4K 160hz. Most people are still on 1080P panels, and even in more enthusiast circles for PC hardware, most people are still running 1440P 144hz/1080 240hz. A 3070 is enough to run most games maxed at over 120 fps in 1440p(and even 4K in many titles) and most of the performance issues are due to poor optimization, which is a game dev problem. 

So I do think that going forward, lower end SKUs will probably be very popular but once the market saturates with these low end cards that out speed 3090s, I think GPU sales will stall out or even decline unless a lot more people get into the PC building scene. 

I do think that a small number of people will certainly still be getting the fastest cards but games already don't look a whole lot better going from medium/high to Ultra/RTX and GPUs are already getting a bit ridiculous in speed. I am not advocating for not getting that performance, I honestly want all the performance we can get. The problem also exists with CPUs to an extent. Everything that is a 8700K or better for Intel and a 5600X or better for AMD far exceeds the CPU use of any game at any existing resolution/refresh rate and those are the bottom of the barrel parts. Anything that is a 12700K/5900X or better probably will still be usable 7-8 years from now without any real loss in performance aside from being on DDR4 versus DDR5 or even DDR6 eventually.  This will come into full effect with mature DDR5 CPUs, where those things may legitimately end up seeing 10+ year use cycles as a somewhat common occurrence. 

We have the technology right now to make 4K 480hz monitors. DP 2.1 supports it and we are soon due for another iteration of display port which should increase it enough that 4K 480hz wouldn't even require the use of DSC to accomplish. At the very least, 4K 240hz should be a thing already. The only reason it appears to not yet exist is because many of the big monitor brands want to milk each and every bump in resolution/refresh rate as much as possible where charging 700-1000 USD for a monitor is becoming common place. This is going to stall out a lot of people from upgrading for a very long time, as it would mean replacing their entire system to run a new monitor and spending like 3000-4000+ to look at the same games in a slightly better image. Casuals are fine with 1440P 144hz(300 dollars) and competitive sweats are fine with 1080p TN 240hz(300) and both commonly go on sale, a small number of people upgraded to 1440p 240(problem with these is that 27 inches is too big for comp fps) and 4K 144.

People won't upgrade til its cheaper to do so, but for it to become cheaper, companies need not charge so much and they need more volume of sales. But neither are happening so prices remain high and adoption is low. 

Only way I see this being solved is when 1080P as a resolution is just completely done away with and that won't happen for another 10 years or more. All the FPS nerds(like me) are mostly fine with 25 inch 1080P panels that refresh as fast as possible, 360hz now(480hz and up tomorrow), and then all the panels that get down binned at a discount to 240hz or 144hz...people will just buy those. There needs to be 24-25 inch 1440p/4K panels at 240hz and up at competitive prices to get the adoption of higher resolutions up.

Monitor manufactures are just addicted to making them very expensive and getting larger margins on each unit as compared with the TV industry where for the most part, all those affordable TVs are razer thin margins.

author: @MooresLawIsDead
comments:
If only the node was required for improvements...TSMC wouldn't need Nvidia and AMD. :)

Think of it this way - every new node brings improved "tools" for "building" a better card.  It's up to AMD and Nvidia to decide how to best build this new card.  If they do a good job, they build something that exceeds TSMC's expectations, if they do bad...well you get something like Fermi lol.  But at this point, honestly, both of these companies are really good at utilizing the latest tools effectively every generation.  They're not amateurs.

I am not "dismissing" architectures' importance in this video, I am simply focusing on how the node itself dictates a rough ballpark of performance...and as you can see in this video....the expectations TSMC dictates are usually pretty close to the reality of the final performance.

comments: One problem: You said Samsung's 8nm and TSMC's 7nm are similar density-wise. But in reality, TSMC's 7nm is much denser. GA102 vs N21: 45.1 vs 51.5 M / mmÂ²
GA104 vs N22: 44.4 vs 51.3 M / mmÂ²
GA106 vs N23: 43.5 vs 46.7 M / mmÂ²

Look at Pascal
GP100: 25.1M / mmÂ²
GP102: 25.1M / mmÂ²
GP104: 22.9M / mmÂ²
GP106: 22.0M / mmÂ²
GP108: 24.3M / mmÂ²
They aren't that far off, AMD didn't go full throttle on max performance at the cost of some density. They both chose different design choices, but they more or less are the same transistor density per mmÂ²

author: @joshdau
comments:
Doesn't this analysis completely ignore any performance gains from architectural improvement? What you've outlined here is a possible baseline improvement gen-to-gen if all NVIDIA did was copy and paste the Ampere design to a new node, and update the power and frequency curve to get the most out of it. It completely ignores any gains in performance that come from changes to the underlying architecture, like the addition of more ALUs, changes to those ALUs to improve throughput, or even more fundamental changes like we saw in the GCN to RDNA transition.

I agree that a 200% performance gain over Ampere is likely overhyping what's possible, however if - based on your analysis - NVIDIA could get double the performance of Ampere by simply shrinking the node, then it's not unexpected to think they could get 120-150% over Ampere by combining that with some architectural improvements.

For example, take RDNA1 vs RDNA2. Both of these were manufactured on the same node, yet were able to extract around 20% improvements from architectural changes alone (die size for die size).

EDIT: With all that said, I think the analysis here is misleading, which I go into more detail in on one of my replies under this comment. To be able to extrapolate performance like this, you'd need to isolate the performance gains made from node improvements in the previous generations compared, from the improvements from other changes, and that hasn't been done here. Instead, the numbers are fudged a little to correlate foundry node improvement claims with previous generational improvements, which whilst close, looks to be fairly coincidental given how many other factors go into the underlying performance of a generation of GPU.

author: @TheGuruStud
comments: No, b/c you're also comparing to historical IPC improvement, which Nvidia never does huge gains. They just throw more shader cores at it. Take a look at Maxwell to paxwell to turding to ampoo. It's literally zero gains or Intel level ðŸ¤£. It's virtually all brute force.

author: @joshdau
comments:
@@TheGuruStud Except this analysis isn't doing that. This analysis is first purporting that all of the previous improvements (ie Maxwell to Pascal) came purely from node improvements, by first trying to establish a strict correlation between performance across generation to the performance claims TSMC/Samsung make, and then attempts to extrapolate the performance of future cards relying solely on improvements in the node technology.

It doesn't work like that, the previous generations improvements came from a combination of node and architectural changes, and any similarity between the gen-to-gen performance improvements and the claimed node improvements is coincidental at best, or a fudging of numbers to over exaggerate/overstate a correlation at worst.

Whilst I usually agree with almost everything MLID says, and I guess the "heart" in what he is trying to say here, in order to make the analysis that MLID is trying to make here you'd need to isolate the performance improvements in previous generations out from changes in architecture, compare that to the claims of the foundries, and then use that to extrapolate a rough guess at where this would take us in the next generation.

author: @joshdau
comments:
â€‹@Start Finish I agree with most of what you say, except I don't really think that's the claim that Tom is making in this video.

He goes to quite extensive lengths to compare the generational improvements of previous GPU releases with the foundry performance improvements, making it out to be an almost one to one correlation. The foundry node performance improvement numbers come purely from their ability to clock higher at lower voltages - they don't factor in anything architecturally (architectural improvements come from the ability to include more logic in the same die area).

So to say that the Maxwell to Pascal improvements was roughly 60% and then show that the expected improvement based on the node numbers from the foundry should also be roughly 60% is disingenuous, it completely ignores the fact that there are architectural changes mixed in with the previous generations improvements.

A better analysis would have taken the Maxwell to Pascal gen-on-gen improvements, attempted to remove the % increase in performance due to architectural changes, and then compared the remaining % improvements with the foundry numbers, and THEN extrapolate what that means for the next generation. Except that wasn't done here.

author: @benc3825
comments:
Chiplets donâ€™t save a massive amount of  edge silicon. Sure, you can have a larger total amount of silicon on a single package, but you can optimize each piece of silicon for what it will be used for.
A compute die? Optimize for performance on the fastest node.
Cache die and/or an I/O die? Optimize for density and energy efficiency on a cheaper node using extra silicon

It isnâ€™t possible to do that level of customization with a simple monolithic die. Look at the 5800X3D as an example. The stock Zen 3 chiplet has 2 separate 16MB banks of L3 cache. With a density optimized node, they can. Add 2 separate 32MB dies on top of each of the 16MB. They tripled cache, but only doubled the total silicon used on cache.

author: @TrueThanny
comments:
The performance increase figures are talking about clock speed.  You can't do the comparison the way you are.  You're not accounting for the difference in performance caused by having more ALU's, from one generation to the next, or the difference in clock speeds.

If a node shrink is supposed to provide the same performance at 50% reduced power, that means you can double the number of ALU's while running at the same clock speed and consuming the same amount of power.  That net's you a doubling of performance, despite the fact that you're taking advantage of the power savings of the node, not the performance increase.

And when you increase ALU count and increase frequency, you're doing a mix of the two.

In no way can you compare the relative gaming performance of two GPU's and compare that to TSMC's "performance" claims for a node.

author: @joshdau
comments:
Yea, 100%.  This is what I came here to comment. This analysis assumes that NVIDIA just takes Ampere, puts it on a new node, and then increases the clocks / power until it hits their targets. The performance outlined here gives a baseline performance increase based on the capabilities of the new node, but completely ignores any performance increases brought through changes to the architecture. Going by this logic, were the improvements in performance from GCN to RDNA purely from node shrinks? You can't turn around and say that "Oh no, in that instance, the performance improvements came from the new architecture", whilst simultaneously ignoring architectural changes in this analysis.

Now, do I think a 3x performance increase is correct? No way. I do believe that the ~100% performance increase gen-over-gen is what we should be expecting, but I do believe that a significant contributor to the increase in performance between generations of GPUs was completely overlooked here, and it's possible that with some smart utilisation of the extra die space NVIDIA will get from going from 8nm to 4nm this generation, that they could get to ~150% performance improvements gen-on-gen without resorting to anything insane, especially if they plan to increase power consumption to compensate for the increase in transistor count.

comments: @@joshdau I don't think nVidia will even hit a 100% increase, either.  I just find any "analysis" done with fundamentally flawed assumptions to be pointless.  He was trying to use numbers to disprove what's almost certainly a bad claim, but he may as well have been reading tea leaves, since the numbers he used have no tether to the topic at hand.

My claim for 120-150% improvements were made on the basis that we assume the claim of 80-100% purely from node improvements from the video was based on fact, which for a number of different reasons isn't likely to be the case.

author: @photonboy999
comments:
He discussed this as "Naveen Veeravalli" also says.
Generally I wouldn't use "IPC" to discuss GPU's but the layperson just conflates "IPC gains" with performance gains. When he talks about RASTERIZATION he's talking about typical, non-gaming, non-AI upscaling performance which is pretty much every game made before a few years ago and most games still today. There's a BALANCE to be struck between Rasterization, AI- upscaling and Ray-tracing. NVidia could have EASILY had way more ray-tracing hardware in the RTX "20" cards but then less transistors would have been available for typical game rendering... and AI-upscaling is great but it's not Universal. If NVidia gets AI upscaling working easily on OLDER games (similar to DLDSR) then it gets easier to justify a budget towards AI upscaling which in turn can free up performance to make ray-tracing work.
Anyway, you can talk about performance-per-Watt or whatever you want but it's basically "IPC gains" to the layman. What matters most to the average user will be performance in YOUR budget, the Wattage drawn, ray-tracing performance, AI upscaling (software solutions and hardware performance) and various other features such as video encoders/decoders etc. Some people will mostly care about performance per dollar.

author: @ayyveezee2079
comments: Pascal took the hardware scheduler out, solely software scheduling, big power savings. Turing put hardware scheduling back in, thus somewhat lacklust power/performance in combo with Samsung 12nm.

author: @LiveType
comments:
Pulling out the hardware scheduler happened I believe with maxwell. It's what allowed for such massive efficiency gains at the expensive of greater cpu overhead which nvidia bet on not being an issue as cpus got more powerful. Cleary that didn't really happen so the hardware scheduler was put back in for turing due to the significantly more complex architecture. Turing should have been designed around ~2015 so the timeline makes sense. Not sure if that was the major reason it was put back in but it was definitely one of them. The overhead even now with the hybrid design is not insignificant as hardware unboxed showed. It is overall way better than AMD's though. That's undeniable. So what if you can hit high framerates if they aren't consistent? That's what a lot of congestion algorithms do. They trade a not insignificant amount of peak performance for improved consistency.

I can 100% see nvidia pulling it back out to claw back some efficiency and splitting their gpus lines up even more for more specialization for the sub $500 market. That becomes a nightmare to manage though. Imagine the driver bundle size. It's going to hit like 1.5-2GB in ~3 years. Remember 200MB gpu driver bundles?

author: @stuporman
comments:
guys, it actually happened with Kepler, that's why it was so efficient compared to Fermi. they got away with it for a long time because games were still using DX11.
proper DX12/vulkan games use completely different way of programming with async compute so software scheduler doesn't cut it anymore. that's my take anyway, it could be that scheduling can be done on CPUs once again since they're much faster than 10 years ago and nvidia can get away with decoupling the scheduler.

author: @Psychx_
comments: What's the deal with Nvidia always demanding custom nodes in lithography? Isn't it hell of expensive and time consuming to set up, while delivering nearly insignificant benefits?

author: @pilerks1
comments: I have a feelings its more marketing than anything. I'm no expert, but I'd assume much of the manufacturing of these "custom" nvidia nodes is the same as the public manufacturing process

author: @andersjjensen
comments: It's not "demanding". It's working with your foundry. AMD does the same. So does Apple. The standard nodes are for the small fish. And yes, it is costly. But with wafer prices of $16,000 a pop and die sizes of 600mm2 it is worth investing in even 2-5% gains in either area or voltage/frequency scaling.

author: @benc3825
comments:
@@pilerks1 They can optimize the node for their specific use case. N5, N5P, N4, N4P, and N4X are basically the same node with minor tweaks to in more EUV layers, higher density, better performance, lower power consumption, etc. When you make a custom node, you can tweak the silicon a ton more. You can make performance scale at higher voltages and other things that are above my pay grade to know.

If you only have a single monolithic die, what else can do to get a slightly better performance? Increase power consumption, core frequency, memory frequency and what else? That is the main issue, what else can you do once the silicon is locked in stone? You don't have time to re-engineer  the silicon die within a year, that is WAY to complex to be done quickly. You can do little silicon level optimizations, but not much. However, if you change the lithography node, as long as you don't "break the design rules. THAT is a change that can be done much quicker and is as close to plug and play as you can get with silicon.

author: @pilerks1
comments: @@benc3825 I see. Thank you for the insight

author: @rarrawer
comments:
One user making thousands of requests for personal data in a day is going to either be a shared account or a bot.
If I was the one making the requests, I'd also be caching results locally to avoid incurring extra fees. 
Similarly I'd also be sharing the info I have with sister organizations, especially if we had an understanding of mutual access. 
Naturally I'd be caching that too; and by caching I mean I'd make permanent copies.
There would also be aggregation of all data sources to build better profiles.

Incidentally if me and a few buddies in other orgs were to be doing this then I would very neatly be sidestepping the effects of anny legal orders to delete / destroy information; since the information the other orgs have is outside my control. I only understand and control the information in the systems I administer, after all. What information other people hold outside my control and awareness that they might decide to grant me access to later is purely a speculative hypothetical that is much harder to act upon, if they had legal standing against those hypothetical others to begin with.

Twisty thinking and complex systems can be a lot of FUN.

author: @XSpImmaLion
comments:
I still don't understand why people think Telegram is any safer than any other alternative. It's worse than WhatsApp from a technical standpoint, you know? It's somewhat on par with Facebook chat, but only barely.
Facebook chat has a p2p encryption option using Signal protocol, but you have to enable it... whereas Telegram also has a p2p encryption option using their own encryption method - but again, you need to turn it on, and it's stupidly shoved into one of the most unintuitive menus I've ever seen in any chat app. I bet most Telegram users don't even know how to turn it on, or that it's even there in the first place.
Just use Signal people. Or Whatsapp. Whatsapp might look bad because it's owned by Facebook, but it's still among the few always on p2p encryption chats out there. And yes, Facebook will harvest every bit of metadata they can out of it, but at least it's not handing message content straight to authorities - because it can't.

author: @garethballard2159
comments: @@genuinennessbefitting4734 Part of this is chip design and who has ordered production. What's also missing from all of this is the role of IBM.

author: @genuinennessbefitting4734
comments: @@garethballard2159 IBM can only design chips in the laboratory. In the chip industry, mass production is a crucial technology. The technology in the laboratory is not tricky. When IBM was bluffing about its 2 nm technology, The TSMC laboratory could already produce 2 nm long before. In 2000, IBM sold its laboratory copper process to UMC. Mass production was impossible at all in actual production, which led to UMC's failure to TSMC in advanced wafers. UMC finally gave up the research and development of advanced processes. TSMC started the risk trial production of 3nm Intel GPU in March 2021. 2 NM was trial-produced in the R&D plant two months ago. TSMC's R&D plant can produce 55,000 pieces, while Samsung's 5 NM mass-produced only 5,000 pieces. The definition of R&D of TSMC is the definition of mass production of other factories.

author: @genuinennessbefitting4734
comments: @@garethballard2159 If euv is the key to manufacturing advanced chips, Samsung, Intel, and other companies can buy euv without hindrance; why is tsmc the only company that can produce 3nm? What's more, ASML's first large order came from TSMC, and euv developed jointly using tsmc's wet immersion technology at tsmc's F12b headquarters in Hsinchu, Taiwan. tsmc invested 1 million wafers and billions of dollars in completing euv research and development.
